ly favorable.", "reasoning": "The research states that glutamate-5-semialdehyde 'spontaneously cyclizes to form \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C).' This spontaneous cyclization is well-documented in biochemistry and does not require enzymatic catalysis, making it prebiotically very plausible. P5C is identified as 'a branch point for the synthesis of proline, glutamate, and arginine.'"}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Reduction of P5C to L-proline", "inputs": ["mol_022", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "330-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Fe2+ ions or transition metal reductants", "aqueous": true, "other": "anoxic conditions, H2 or Fe2+ as electron donor, possibly in hydrothermal vent effluent"}, "mechanism": "The C=N imine bond of \u0394\u00b9-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) is reduced by H2 or Fe2+-mediated electron transfer to yield the saturated secondary amine of L-proline. This is analogous to the biological P5C reductase reaction but driven by abiotic reductants.", "reasoning": "The research describes this as the final step of the proto-metabolic pathway: 'The reduction of P5C by H2 or transition metal ions (e.g., Fe2+) yields proline.' This reaction mirrors the biological P5C reductase step and represents a seamless transition from geochemistry to biochemistry. The autotrophic pathway 'aligns with the core biosynthetic logic found in all kingdoms of life' (Stubbs & Moran, 2020-2022)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Cyanosulfidic pathway (Sutherland) \u2014 direct from HCN + acetylene", "description": "The primary cyanosulfidic route using HCN and acetylene as starting materials under UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox conditions. Proceeds through acrylonitrile, reductive homologation to 2-aminopentanedinitrile, intramolecular cyclization to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, and hydrolysis to proline. This is the most experimentally validated surface pathway.", "r