\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.83,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n            \"feedback\": \"The proto-metabolic pathway via reductive amination is well-aligned with Stubbs & Moran (2020-2022) work on abiotic r-TCA cycle analogs. The aldol condensation of pyruvate and glyoxylate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate is experimentally demonstrated. Reductive amination to glutamate is well-established. The weakest step is rxn_018 (partial reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde), which requires selective reduction of the carboxylate to aldehyde without over-reduction\u2014a challenging transformation prebiotically. Spontaneous cyclization to P5C (rxn_019) is well-documented. Hydrothermal \u2192 Biochemical flow is appropriate. This pathway most closely mirrors biological proline biosynthesis.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify a mineral catalyst or reducing agent for selective glutamate reduction (e.g., Fe2+ or pyrite)\", \"Consider whether ATP or polyphosphate analogs could drive the selective reduction\", \"Address L-specificity\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_003\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_004\": 0.75,\n                \"rxn_005\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_007\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_018\": 0.68,\n                \"rxn_019\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_020\": 0.75\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.79,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.83,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.82,\n            \"feedback\": \"Similar to P5 but uses transamination with glycine instead of reductive amination. Literature reports 44% yield for transamination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate with glycine at 80\u00b0C with AlK(SO4)2. Requires glycine availability, which adds a dependency. The transamination step is well-supported experimentally. Same weakness at rxn_018 as P5.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify glycine source explicitly within the network\", \"Consider AlK(SO4)2 or other mineral catalysts for transamination\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_002\": 0.70,\n                \"rxn_008\": 0.45,\n                \"rxn_012\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_003\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_004\": 0.75,\n                \"rxn_005\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_007\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_018\": 0.68,\n                \"rxn_019\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_020\": 0.75\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.80,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n            \"feedback\": \"The longest pathway spanning all three environments. The full chain from CO2 to glycine (via hydrothermal \u2192 surface Strecker) to proline (via transamination and proto-metabolic route) is conceptually elegant and represents true systems chemistry. However, it inherits the problematic rxn_008 and is vulnerable to cumulative yield losses across 11 steps. The convergent use of glycine as both a product and a reagent in transamination is a nice feature.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_018\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Fix HCN generation step\", \"Consider yield implications of 11-step pathway\"]\n        },\n        {\n   