he hydrothermal origin steps for completeness\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_009\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_010\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_011\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_013\": 0.72,\n                \"rxn_014\": 0.58,\n                \"rxn_015\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_016\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_017\": 0.78\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.81,\n            \"feedback\": \"The convergent pathway demonstrating two independent routes to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile is a strength of the network design. The cyanosulfidic arm is strong; the Strecker arm has the rxn_014 weakness. The convergence at mol_012 is chemically meaningful and well-supported by literature.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Strengthen the Strecker arm by decomposing rxn_014\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"This is a well-designed and comprehensive synthesis network for L-proline that closely follows the current state of prebiotic chemistry literature. The three major routes (cyanosulfidic, Strecker, proto-metabolic) are all discussed in the literature and are appropriately represented. Key strengths: (1) Excellent network topology with 23 molecules, 20 reactions, 10 pathways, and 6 convergence points. (2) Hub molecules are well-chosen and properly connected, with HCN and formaldehyde serving as critical distribution nodes. (3) The convergence at pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile from two independent routes is chemically meaningful. (4) Strong alignment with Sutherland cyanosulfidic work and Stubbs/Moran proto-metabolic studies. (5) The environmental flow from hydrothermal CO2 fixation through surface chemistry to biochemical maturation is logical and well-justified. Key weaknesses: (1) rxn_008 (formaldehyde + NH3 \u2192 HCN) is chemically questionable\u2014this is not a standard or well-supported HCN production mechanism. (2) rxn_014 (glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde + NH3 \u2192 4-aminobutanal) is oversimplified and needs decomposition into elementary steps. (3) rxn_018 (selective reduction of glutamate to semialdehyde) lacks a specified mineral catalyst. (4) The L-specificity of proline is not addressed by any reaction in the network\u2014all routes produce racemic proline. The literature discusses proline's role in chiral amplification but this is not incorporated. (5) Some surface reactions lack mineral catalyst specifications. Despite these issues, the network represents a high-quality synthesis plan with multiple viable pathways to the target.\",\n    \"approved\": true,\n    \"hub_quality\": 0.90,\n    \"convergence_quality\": 0.88\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_009": 0.9, "rxn_010": 0.85, "rxn_011": 0.85, "rxn_017": 0.78}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.87, "pathway_coherence": 0.92, "environmental_progression": 0.8, "target_achievement": 0.88, "overall_confidence": 0.87, "feedback": "The cyanosulfidic route is the strongest pathway in the network, directly supported by the Sutherland group literature. Cu(I)-catalyzed coupling of HCN and acetylene to acrylonitrile is well-documented. Reductive homologation with H2S, cyclization, and nitrile hydrolysis are all sound. Minor concern: rxn_017 yields racemic proline, not specifically L-proline; the L-designation requires a chiral symmetry-breaking mechanism not explicitly modeled. Environmental progression is Surface \u2192 Biochemical which is acceptable but lacks the hydrothermal origin stage.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_017"], "suggestions": 