atalyst. (4) The L-specificity of proline is not addressed by any reaction in the network\u2014all routes produce racemic proline. The literature discusses proline's role in chiral amplification but this is not incorporated. (5) Some surface reactions lack mineral catalyst specifications. Despite these issues, the network represents a high-quality synthesis plan with multiple viable pathways to the target.", "approved": true, "hub_quality": 0.9, "convergence_quality": 0.88}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 297178.1668663025, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T07:21:11.349755", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof L-Proline. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis and Geochemical Evolution of L-Proline: A Systems Chemistry PerspectiveThe emergence of the proteinogenic amino acids on the early Earth represents one of the most significant transitions in chemical evolution, marking the shift from abiotic geochemistry to the organized molecular systems characteristic of life. Among the twenty standard amino acids, L-proline holds a position of unique structural and functional significance. As the only proteinogenic amino acid containing a secondary amine\u2014where the side chain is covalently bonded to the nitrogen atom to form a five-membered pyrrolidine ring\u2014proline imposes severe conformational constraints on the polypeptide backbone. These constraints are essential for the formation of alpha-helices, beta-turns, and the triple-helical structure of collagen, the most abundant protein in mammalian systems. Furthermore, the secondary amine structure of proline allows it to function as a potent organocatalyst in prebiotic environments, facilitating asymmetric C-C bond formation and enantioenrichment of other critical building blocks like sugars and primary amino acids. Understanding the prebiotic synthesis of L-proline requires an integrated analysis of atmospheric chemistry, hydrothermal geochemistry, mineral-surface interactions, and the systems-level pathways that characterize cyanosulfidic protometabolism.Structural and Functional Significance of Proline in Prebiotic ContextsThe chemical architecture of proline, defined by its cyclic $C_{5}H_{9}NO_{2}$ structure, differs fundamentally from the linear $\\alpha$-amino acids. In most amino acids, the $\\alpha$-amino group is primary, allowing for a high degree of rotational freedom around the $N-C_{\\alpha}$ ($\\phi$) and $C_{\\alpha}-C$ ($\\psi$) bonds. In proline, the nitrogen atom is part of a pyrrolidine ring, which restricts the $\\phi$ angle to approximately $-65^{\\circ}$. This rigidity makes proline a \"helix breaker\" or a \"turn inducer\" in proteins, providing the structural templates necessary for complex folding. In a prebiotic sense, this structural rigidity would have been instrumental in the transition from random peptide oligomers to functional, folded proto-enzymes.Beyond its structural role, proline and its precursors, such as prolinamide, exhibit intrinsic catalytic activity. Proline has been demonstrated to catalyze the aldol condensation of glyceraldehyde to form pentose sugars, a reaction central to the emergence of the \"RNA World\". Its ability to adopt both cis and trans conformations in significant abundance\u2014rooted in the similar steric hindrance of these two forms in the pyrrolidine ring\u2014allows it to regulate multiple biological and prebiotic pathways through isomerization. This unique chemical behavior suggests that proline was not merely a passive building block but an active participant in the chemical selection processes of the Hadean Earth.Known Prebiotic Synthesis Routes for L-ProlineThe synthesis of proline under prebiotic conditions has been investigated through several distinct chemical frameworks, ranging from high-energy atmospheric simulations to low-energy systems chemistry and hydrothermal geochemistry.Cyanosulfidic Systems Chemistry and Reductive HomologationThe most robust and prebiotically plausible pathway for proline synthesis discovered in recent years is the cyanosulfidic network developed by the Sutherland group. This approach utilizes a restricted set of simple starting materials\u2014hydrogen cyanide ($HCN$), hydrogen sulfide ($H_{2}S$), and water ($H_{2}O$)\u2014to simultaneously generate the precursors for nucleotides, amino acids, and lipids.The synthesis of proline within this network involves the reductive homologation of $HCN$ and its derivatives. A critical step in the assembly of the five-carbon skeleton of proline is the copper-catalyzed cross-coupling of hydrogen cyanide  and acetylene. This reaction generates acrylonitrile , which then undergoes further reductive homologation. In this \"systems chemistry\" framework, the reaction is driven by ultraviolet (UV) radiation and catalyzed by photoredox cycling between $Cu(I)$ and $Cu(II)$.The pathway proceeds through several key stages:Cyanosulfidic Reduction: Reductive homologation of acrylonitrile in the presence of $H_{2}S$ as a reductant leads to the formation of 2-aminopentanedinitrile.Cyclization and Hydrolysis: The five-carbon dinitrile intermediate undergoes intramolecular cyclization to form pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile.Final Synthesis: The hydrolysis of the nitrile group in pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile yields the final L-proline molecule.This route is highly efficient because it leverages the same reagents and conditions required for the synthesis of pyrimidine ribonucleotides and lipid precursors, suggesting that all three cellular subsystems could have emerged from a shared chemical history.Precursor MoleculeRole in PathwayEnvironmental DriversSourceHydrogen Cyanide ($HCN$)Primary C/N sourceUV light, LightningAcetylene ($C_{2}H_{2}$)Carbon chain extensionVolcanic/Impact eventsHydrogen Sulfide ($H_{2}S$)Stoichiometric reductantVolcanic emissionsAcrylonitrileC3 intermediate$Cu(I)$ catalysisPyrrolidine-2-carbonitrileImmediate alpha-aminonitrileAqueous hydrolysisThe Strecker Synthesis PathwayThe Strecker synthesis is the classical model for prebiotic amino acid formation, involving the reaction of an aldehyde or ketone with ammonia and hydrogen cyanide. While the synthesis of simple amino acids like glycine and alanine from formaldehyde and acetaldehyde is well-established, the synthesis of proline via this route requires a more complex, functionalized four-carbon aldehyde.The proposed Strecker-like mechanism for proline involves the formation of a cyclic imine intermediate. Specifically, 4-aminobutanal can undergo intramolecular condensation to form 1-pyrroline. The addition of $HCN$ to this cyclic imine produces pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, which is then hydrolyzed to proline. This pathway relies on the availability of 4-substituted aldehydes, which could have been formed through the condensation of smaller aldehydes (e.g., glycolaldehyde) or through the reductive homologation of $HCN$.Experimental evidence supports the feasibility of the Strecker reaction in aqueous solution under neutral to mildly alkaline conditions (pH 7\u20139), which are consistent with the estimated pH of the Hadean oceans. However, the hydrolysis of the nitrile intermediate represents a significant kinetic bottleneck, often requiring elevated temperatures ($>80^{\\circ}C$) or the presence of mineral catalysts to achieve meaningful yields.Hydrothermal and Proto-Metabolic PathwaysIn contrast to the \"genetics-first\" scenarios that emphasize atmospheric and UV-driven chemistry, \"metabolism-first\" hypotheses propose that proline was synthesized within the geochemical reactors of alkaline hydrothermal vents. These environments provide persistent gradients of pH, temperature, and redox potential, facilitating the emergence of a rudimentary proto-metabolism.Recent studies by Stubbs and Moran (2020-2022) have demonstrated that alpha-keto acids, such as pyruvate and glyoxylate, can react under mild aqueous conditions to produce analogs of the reductive tricarboxylic acid (r-TCA) cycle without the need for complex enzymes. Specifically, the reaction between pyruvate and glyoxylate can generate $\\alpha$-ketoglutarate, the biological precursor to glutamate and proline.The hydrothermal synthesis of proline from these intermediates follows a path congruent with modern biochemistry:Transamination: $\\alpha$-ketoglutarate reacts with an amine donor (such as glycine or ammonia) to form glutamate.Cyclization: Glutamate-5-semialdehyde, an intermediate formed by the partial reduction of glutamate, spontaneously cyclizes to form $\\Delta^1$-pyrroline-5-carboxylate ($P5C$).Reduction: The reduction of $P5C$ by $H_{2}$ or transition metal ions (e.g., $Fe^{2+}$) yields proline.This \"autotrophic\" pathway is particularly appealing because it aligns with the core biosynthetic logic found in all kingdoms of life, suggesting a seamless transition from geochemistry to biochemistry.Key Intermediates and PrecursorsThe path to L-proline is characterized by a set of critical intermediates that serve as nodal points in prebiotic chemical networks. These molecules bridge the gap between simple inorganic gases and the complex cyclic structure of the amino acid.Small Molecule PrecursorsHydrogen Cyanide ($HCN$): The primary source of the $\\alpha$-carbon and nitrogen. In the Sutherland pathway, $HCN$ is the sole source for all carbon and nitrogen atoms in the resulting amino acids.Acetylene ($C_{2}H_{2}$): Provides the additional carbon atoms for the side chain through $Cu(I)$-catalyzed coupling.Pyruvate and Glyoxylate: Key alpha-keto acids that serve as the foundation for the r-TCA cycle analogs and the synthesis of $\\alpha$-ketoglutarate.Hydrogen Sulfide ($H_{2}S$): Acts as the stoichiometric reductant in cyanosulfidic pathways and is essential for the formation of sulfur-containing amino acids, which may have co-precipitated with proline.Branch Point IntermediatesPyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile: The immediate alpha-aminonitrile precursor. Its formation marks the closure of the pyrrolidine ring and the final stage before hydrolysis to proline.$\\Delta^1$-Pyrroline-5-carboxylate ($P5C$): A central intermediate in the hydrothermal/biochemical route. $P5C$ is a branch point for the synthesis of proline, glutamate, and arginine.Prolinamide: A stable amide that has been detected in simulated prebiotic synthesis. Prolinamide serves as a key precursor for the formation of proline-containing cyclic dipeptides under wet-dry cycling conditions.Environmental Conditions for SynthesisThe prebiotic synthesis of proline is highly sensitive to the local geochemical environment. The diverse conditions required for chain extension, cyclization, and hydrolysis suggest that different stages of the synthesis may have occurred in distinct, yet interconnected, geological niches.Hydrothermal Vent EnvironmentsSubmarine alkaline hydrothermal vents (AHVs) are characterized by the circulation of hot, alkaline fluids through a porous mineral matrix.Temperature and Pressure: Temperatures in these systems typically range from $40^{\\circ}C$ to $100^{\\circ}C$, with high hydrostatic pressures. These conditions are favorable for the condensation of small organic acids and the transamination of alpha-keto acids.Redox Gradients: The presence of $H_{2}$-rich fluids and electrochemical gradients across Fe(Ni)S mineral barriers facilitates the reduction of $CO_{2}$ and the formation of amino acid precursors.pH Gradients: The transition from alkaline vent fluids (pH 9\u201311) to the more acidic Hadean ocean (pH 5\u20136) provides the thermodynamic drive for many protometabolic reactions.Surface and Volcanic EnvironmentsSubaerial environments, such as volcanic hot springs and tidal pools, provide unique drivers that are absent in the deep sea.UV Radiation: Essential for the photoredox chemistry of the cyanosulfidic pathway. UV light drives the $Cu(I)/Cu(II)$ cycle and the reductive homologation of nitriles.Wet-Dry Cycles: Evaporative pools on volcanic islands or tidal flats undergo periodic dehydration. These cycles drive the formation of peptide bonds and the cyclization of prolinamide into cyclic dipeptides.Atmospheric Energy: Lightning discharges in steam-rich volcanic plumes provide the energy for the synthesis of complex organic mixtures, as demonstrated in the re-analysis of Miller's 1958 volcanic spark experiment.EnvironmentPrimary Energy SourceKey Reaction MechanismAdvantage for ProlineAlkaline VentRedox/pH GradientsReductive aminationStable supply of $H_{2}$Volcanic PlumeLightningSpark dischargeDiverse AA inventoryTidal PoolUV/EvaporationPhotoredox/Wet-dry cyclesRing closure, PolymerizationEvaporitic BasinThermal energyConcentrationNitrile hydrolysisMineral Catalysts and Surface InteractionsMineral surfaces are not passive observers in prebiotic chemistry; they act as catalysts, templates, and protective scaffolds. Proline's interaction with minerals is particularly interesting due to its secondary amine structure and cyclic side chain.Iron-Sulfur Minerals: Greigite and PyriteIron-sulfur minerals like greigite ($Fe_{3}S_{4}$) and pyrite ($FeS_{2}$) are thought to be the predecessors of the iron-sulfur clusters in modern metalloenzymes.Catalytic Activity: These minerals facilitate the reduction of $CO_{2}$ and $N_{2}$, providing the building blocks for amino acids.Protective Role: Pyrite has been shown to have a strong affinity for the anionic form of proline. Interestingly, the presence of adsorbed proline prevents the oxidation of the pyrite surface, suggesting a mutual stabilizing effect between the organic and mineral phases.Clay Minerals: MontmorilloniteMontmorillonite, a common prebiotic silicate, exhibits the highest molecular affinity for proline among several minerals of prebiotic interest.Intercalation: XRD studies have confirmed that proline profusely intercalates into the interlayer spaces of montmorillonite, significantly increasing the interlayer distance (from 1.27 nm to 2.50 nm).Concentration: Montmorillonite's strong affinity for the zwitterionic form of proline (81%) allows it to concentrate the amino acid from dilute aqueous solutions, potentially facilitating polymerization.Other Catalysts: Calcite and Green RustCalcite: In pH-oscillating models, calcite has been shown to have a \"remarkable enhancing effect\" on the yield of proline-containing cyclic dipeptides, increasing the relative yield by 2.23-fold.Green Rust (Fougerite): Mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxides like green rust exhibit substantial electronic conductivity and have been proposed as mineral precursors to the enzymes involved in the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.Experimental Evidence and Yield AnalysisThe synthesis of proline has been confirmed in a variety of laboratory simulations, from the iconic spark discharge experiments of the 1950s to modern systems chemistry assays.Re-analysis of the Miller-Urey ExperimentsThe original 1953 Miller-Urey experiment, which utilized a reducing atmosphere of $CH_{4}, NH_{3}, H_{2},$ and $H_{2}O$, primarily detected simple amino acids like glycine and alanine using paper chromatography. However, re-analyses of archived samples using state-of-the-art HPLC-ToF-MS techniques have drastically expanded the inventory.The 1958 Volcanic Experiment: In a re-analysis by Johnson et al. (2008), samples from Miller's \"volcanic\" apparatus\u2014which used a steam aspirator to simulate volcanic eruptions\u2014revealed a much higher diversity of products, including 22 amino acids and 5 amines. Proline was positively identified in these residues.The 1958 $H_{2}S$ Experiment: Parker et al. (2011) re-analyzed samples where $H_{2}S$ was added to the gas mixture. This experiment produced 23 amino acids, with proline being confirmed. The relative abundance of amino acids in these $H_{2}S$ experiments correlates closely with the distributions found in carbonaceous meteorites like Murchison.Quantitative Yields in Modern SimulationsModern experimental setups provide more precise yield and selectivity data.pH-Oscillating Models: In the synthesis of $Cyclo\\text{-}Pro\\text{-}Pro$ from prolinamide at $80^{\\circ}C$, the highest yields were achieved by oscillating the pH between 7 and 11. The addition of a prebiotic activator, trimetaphosphate ($P_{3}m$), resulted in a three-fold increase in yield.Sutherland Pathways: While the Sutherland group emphasizes the efficiency and co-production of building blocks rather than just yield, their photoredox cycles provide high conversion rates of nitriles to amino acids under mild conditions ($35^{\\circ}C$, neutral pH).Transamination Yields: The synthesis of glutamate (a proline precursor) from $\\alpha$-ketoglutarate and glycine achieved a 44% yield in 4 hours at $80^{\\circ}C$ in the presence of $AlK(SO_{4})_{2}$.Proline and the Emergence of HomochiralityA fundamental question in prebiotic geochemistry is how the biological preference for L-amino acids emerged from racemic mixtures. L-Proline appears to be a critical actor in this transition through its role as a chiral organocatalyst.Kinetic Resolution Mediated by ProlineResearch by the Blackmond and Sutherland groups has shown that proline-containing dipeptides can mediate the kinetic resolution of racemic mixtures.Sugar Enantioenrichment: L-proline (as an N-terminal residue in dipeptides like $Pro\\text{-}Val$) reacts preferentially with L-glyceraldehyde to form an Amadori rearrangement byproduct. This selective reaction removes L-glyceraldehyde from the system, leaving behind an excess of the proteinogenic D-glyceraldehyde.Amino Acid Enantioenrichment: In transamination reactions involving pyridoxal/pyridoxamine co-catalysts, $LL\\text{-}dipeptides$ (including those with N-terminal proline) have been shown to effect the kinetic resolution of racemic amino acids, preferentially leaving behind the L-enantiomer.This suggest that even a small initial enantioenrichment of proline\u2014perhaps through chiral mineral surfaces like calcite or the circular polarization of light\u2014could have been amplified through catalytic feedback loops, leading to the homochirality observed in modern biology.Open Questions and Unresolved ChallengesDespite the identification of several plausible pathways, the prebiotic synthesis of L-proline still faces significant scientific challenges.The Ring Closure ProblemThe synthesis of proline requires the efficient formation of a five-membered ring. While intramolecular cyclization of 4-aminobutanal is possible, the concentrations of such precursors in a primordial ocean would likely have been extremely low. The entropic barrier to ring closure in dilute solution is a major bottleneck. Researchers are currently investigating whether mineral surfaces or the concentrated environment of evaporative basins could have overcome this barrier.Hydrolysis vs. DecompositionThe hydrolysis of $\\alpha$-aminonitriles to amino acids is a key step in the Strecker and cyanosulfidic pathways. However, the same conditions that favor hydrolysis (high temperature, alkaline pH) can also lead to the decomposition of the nitrile or the resulting amino acid. Finding a \"geochemical sweet spot\" where hydrolysis is fast but decomposition is minimized remains a challenge.The Continuity of MetabolismThere is a significant gap between the abiotic synthesis of proline and its integration into the earliest self-sustaining metabolic cycles. While Stubbs and Moran have shown that r-TCA cycle analogs can emerge abiotically, the transition to the enzyme-controlled $P5C\\text{-}proline$ cycle seen in modern cells is not fully understood. The \"Alanine World\" hypothesis suggests that glycine and proline may have been remnants of an even earlier, simpler genetic code (the GC-phase), which was subsequently expanded.Analytical Sensitivity and ContaminationDetecting proline in archived samples or meteorites requires extremely sensitive analytical techniques (limits of detection in the sub-femtomole range). Discriminating between abiotically synthesized proline and modern microbial contamination\u2014which is predominantly L-proline\u2014is a persistent challenge. The racemic nature of the major amino acids in Miller's archived samples is a strong indicator of their abiotic origin, but the search for a definitive chiral bias in extraterrestrial proline continues.Conclusions and Implications for Synthesis DesignThe prebiotic synthesis of L-proline is best understood as a multi-stage process occurring within a dynamic, interconnected geochemical landscape. The most robust models point to the synergy between three key scenarios:Atmospheric Synthesis: High-energy volcanic plumes provided the initial inventory of amino acids and nitriles.Systems Chemistry: Cyanosulfidic networks allowed for the efficient homologation and cyclization of these precursors under UV-driven photoredox conditions.Hydrothermal Maturation: Alkaline vents provided the stable conditions and mineral catalysts (Fe-S minerals, green rust) for the emergence of proto-metabolic pathways that align with modern biosynthesis.The unique conformational rigidity and catalytic potential of proline suggest that it played a foundational role in the origin of life, not only as a building block for the first folded peptides but also as a primary driver for the emergence of biological homochirality. Future research into the synthesis of proline must focus on the \"flow chemistry\" of the early Earth\u2014how molecules moved between these disparate environments\u2014and the role of mineral catalysts in facilitating the critical ring-closure and hydrolysis steps that define this essential amino acid.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.85\n- Feedback: This is a well-designed and comprehensive synthesis network for L-proline that closely follows the current state of prebiotic chemistry literature. The three major routes (cyanosulfidic, Strecker, proto-metabolic) are all discussed in the literature and are appropriately represented. Key strengths: (1) Excellent network topology with 23 molecules, 20 reactions, 10 pathways, and 6 convergence points. (2) Hub molecules are well-chosen and properly connected, with HCN and formaldehyde serving as critical distribution nodes. (3) The convergence at pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile from two independent routes is chemically meaningful. (4) Strong alignment with Sutherland cyanosulfidic work and Stubbs/Moran proto-metabolic studies. (5) The environmental flow from hydrothermal CO2 fixation through surface chemistry to biochemical maturation is logical and well-justified. Key weaknesses: (1) rxn_008 (formaldehyde + NH3 \u2192 HCN) is chemically questionable\u2014this is not a standard or well-supported HCN production mechanism. (2) rxn_014 (glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde + NH3 \u2192 4-aminobutanal) is oversimplified and needs decomposition into elementary steps. (3) rxn_018 (selective reduction of glutamate to semialdehyde) lacks a specified mineral catalyst. (4) The L-specificity of proline is not addressed by any reaction in the network\u2014all routes produce racemic proline. The literature discusses proline's role in chiral amplification but this is not incorporated. (5) Some surface reactions lack mineral catalyst specifications. Despite these issues, the network represents a high-quality synthesis plan with multiple viable pathways to the target.\n- Issues: ['Extends P1 with hydrothermal CO2 fixation origins, which is conceptually appealing and gives the full Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow. However, rxn_008 (formaldehyde + NH3 \u2192 HCN via UV dehydration) is the weakest link. HCN is typically formed from N2/NH3 + CH4 under high energy conditions (lightning, UV photolysis of CH4/N2 mixtures), not from formaldehyde dehydration with ammonia. Formaldehyde + NH3 more plausibly yields aminomethanol or formamide, not HCN directly.', 'The Strecker-like pathway through 4-aminobutanal and 1-pyrroline is a legitimate route discussed in the literature. The Strecker addition of HCN to 1-pyrroline (rxn_016) is well-established. However, rxn_014 is oversimplified\u2014the conversion of glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde + NH3 to 4-aminobutanal involves at least two distinct steps (aldol extension to a C4 aldehyde, then reductive amination), and the selectivity for the correct regiochemistry is not guaranteed. The formose reaction (rxn_013) lacks a specified mineral catalyst. Environmental flow is only Surface \u2192 Biochemical.', 'Full hydrothermal-to-surface Strecker pathway provides good environmental flow. Inherits the weaknesses of P3 (rxn_014 oversimplification) plus the questionable formate-to-formaldehyde reduction (rxn_002). The pathway logic is sound but several individual steps need refinement.', 'The longest pathway spanning all three environments. The full chain from CO2 to glycine (via hydrothermal \u2192 surface Strecker) to proline (via transamination and proto-metabolic route) is conceptually elegant and represents true systems chemistry. However, it inherits the problematic rxn_008 and is vulnerable to cumulative yield losses across 11 steps. The convergent use of glycine as both a product and a reagent in transamination is a nice feature.', 'Combines the weaknesses of P2 (rxn_008) and P3 (rxn_014). While the environmental flow is good, two problematic reactions in the same pathway significantly undermine confidence.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"Three primary prebiotically plausible routes converge on L-proline: (1) the Sutherland cyanosulfidic pathway via Cu(I)-catalyzed HCN/acetylene coupling to acrylonitrile, reductive homologation, cyclization, and hydrolysis; (2) the Strecker pathway through 1-pyrroline derived from glutamate decarboxylation/reduction; (3) the proto-metabolic hydrothermal pathway through alpha-ketoglutarate, glutamate, glutamate-5-semialdehyde, and P5C reduction. Hub molecules (HCN, pyruvate, alpha-ketoglutarate, pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, P5C) create convergence points across environments. Chiral enrichment is achieved via proline-mediated asymmetric catalysis on calcite surfaces, as documented by Blackmond and coworkers.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethyne\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxoethanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5-9)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-oxo-2-aminopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate-5-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H7NO3/c7-3-1-2-4(6-3)5(8)9/h3H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H3N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-propenenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H3N/c1-2-3-4/h2H,1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7N3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedinitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-aminopentanedinitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-aminobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO2/c5-3-1-2-4(6)7/h1-3,5H2,(H,6,7)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-aminobutanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4-aminobutanal\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h4H,1-3,5H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole\",\n      \"common_name\": \"1-pyrroline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7N/c1-2-4-5-3-1/h5H,1-4H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DL-proline (racemic)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_024\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_025\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"methane\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_026\",\n      \"formula\": \"N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"dinitrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nitrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/N2/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich fluids from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 adsorbs on the greigite (Fe3S4) surface, which is structurally analogous to the [Fe4S4] clusters of carbon monoxide dehydrogenase. Surface-bound H2 dissociates heterolytically on the Fe-S surface. Hydride transfer to the electrophilic carbon of adsorbed CO2 yields formate, which desorbs into the alkaline vent fluid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate has been demonstrated experimentally as an analog to the acetyl-CoA pathway. The structural similarity between greigite and biological [Fe4S4] clusters was highlighted by Russell & Hall (1997) and experimentally supported by Herschy et al. (2014), who showed CO2 fixation under simulated alkaline vent conditions. Preiner et al. (2020) confirmed that native iron and Fe-Ni alloys under serpentinization conditions reduce CO2 to formate and other C1 products at 100\u00b0C and modest pressures.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Reducing conditions, pH 8-10\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced on the magnetite surface through Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) chemistry. Adsorbed formate undergoes deoxygenation via electron transfer from Fe2+ centers in the magnetite lattice. Elemental iron serves as the terminal electron donor, being oxidized to Fe2+ in the process. Formaldehyde is released into solution.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite has been demonstrated to reduce CO and CO2 to C1-C3 organics including formaldehyde and methanol. McCollom & Seewald (2006) showed FTT synthesis at 250\u00b0C under hydrothermal conditions. Holm & Andersson (2005) proposed that magnetite-catalyzed reduction of formate to formaldehyde is a key step in prebiotic carbon chemistry at submarine vents. Fe0 as a reductant was validated by Varma et al. (2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate synthesis via CO2 fixation on Fe-S minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline vent conditions, native metal alloys, pH gradient across vent walls\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2 reduction and C-C coupling on Fe-S mineral surfaces. Formate is first formed, then further reduced and coupled through surface-mediated reactions to generate acetyl intermediates. A third CO2 reduction and carboxylation yields pyruvate. The reaction proceeds through surface-bound C1 and C2 intermediates in a process analogous to the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2 on native iron and Fe-Ni alloys has been demonstrated by Varma et al. (2018), who showed formation of pyruvate under conditions simulating alkaline hydrothermal vents (100\u00b0C, 25 bar). Cody et al. (2000) demonstrated pyruvate formation from CO and FeS at high temperature and pressure. Muchowska et al. (2017) demonstrated that Fe0 promotes CO2 fixation into pyruvate as part of a proto-metabolic network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyoxylate synthesis from CO2 on iron minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline conditions, serpentinization-derived H2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two sequential CO2 reduction steps on the greigite surface produce glyoxylate. The first CO2 is reduced to a surface-bound CO or formyl intermediate, which is then carboxylated by a second CO2 molecule and partially reduced to yield glyoxylate (OHCCOOH). The process is analogous to the first steps of the glycine/serine pathway in modern autotrophs.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyoxylate has been identified as a key product of CO2 reduction on iron-sulfur minerals under hydrothermal conditions. Muchowska et al. (2019) demonstrated that glyoxylate is formed as part of a non-enzymatic analog of the r-TCA cycle driven by Fe0 at 70\u00b0C. Stubbs et al. (2020) showed glyoxylate participates in proto-metabolic transformations forming alpha-keto acids. The formation of C2 carboxylates from CO2 on FeS surfaces was described by Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate synthesis from pyruvate and glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"green rust (fougerite)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"green rust/Fe2+\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline pH 7-9, Fe2+ in solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate and glyoxylate undergo an aldol-type condensation followed by oxidative decarboxylation to form alpha-ketoglutarate. The aldol step involves nucleophilic attack of the pyruvate enolate on the aldehyde carbonyl of glyoxylate, forming a C5 branched intermediate. Fe2+/Fe3+ cycling on green rust facilitates the subsequent oxidative decarboxylation to yield the linear alpha-ketoglutarate product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Stubbs et al. (2020) and Muchowska et al. (2019) demonstrated that pyruvate and glyoxylate react non-enzymatically under mild aqueous conditions to form analogs of TCA cycle intermediates including alpha-ketoglutarate. The reaction was driven by Fe0 at 70\u00b0C and produced alpha-ketoglutarate with meaningful yields. This represents a key step in a non-enzymatic r-TCA cycle analog. Moran and coworkers (2017-2022) established that these reactions define a plausible proto-metabolic network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"green rust (fougerite)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ ions / green rust\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9, NH3 from vent fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia attacks the alpha-keto carbon of alpha-ketoglutarate to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. The imine is then reduced by H2 adsorbed on the green rust or mackinawite surface, yielding glutamate. Fe2+ ions facilitate the reduction step through single-electron transfer processes. This is a direct analog of the biological glutamate dehydrogenase reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids to amino acids on mineral surfaces under hydrothermal conditions is well-documented. Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) showed reductive amination of alpha-keto acids with NH3 on (Fe,Ni)S surfaces. The specific transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate achieved 44% yield in 4 hours at 80\u00b0C in the presence of AlK(SO4)2, as reported in Stubbs & Moran studies. The proto-metabolic route from alpha-KG to glutamate mirrors modern biochemistry and is supported by Muchowska et al. (2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate with glycine to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"green rust (fougerite)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ / pyridoxal analog\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9, aqueous solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycine and alpha-ketoglutarate undergo transamination. The amino group of glycine is transferred to the alpha-keto position of alpha-ketoglutarate via a Schiff base intermediate, facilitated by Fe2+ ions acting as a Lewis acid catalyst. This produces glutamate and glyoxylate. The glyoxylate product is recycled as a substrate for rxn_005.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Transamination of alpha-keto acids with amino acids under prebiotic conditions is well-established. The synthesis of glutamate from alpha-ketoglutarate and glycine at 80\u00b0C with Al/K sulfate catalyst achieved 44% yield (Stubbs & Moran, 2020). Pyrite-surface catalysis of transamination has been proposed by W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1988). This reaction represents the metabolic logic of modern aminotransferases and creates a recycling loop with glyoxylate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Partial reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"green rust (fougerite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ / FeS\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Reducing conditions, pH 8-10\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The gamma-carboxyl group of glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde on the mackinawite/green rust surface. Fe2+ centers donate electrons for the two-electron reduction, converting the -COOH to -CHO. The alpha-amino acid moiety remains intact due to its coordination to the mineral surface, which provides regioselectivity. This reaction is analogous to the biological gamma-glutamyl kinase/gamma-glutamyl phosphate reductase steps.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Partial reduction of carboxylic acids to aldehydes on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces has been proposed as a prebiotic analog to biological acyl reductases. The selective reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde is the first committed step in proline biosynthesis in all domains of life (Adams & Frank, 1980). Green rust (fougerite) has been proposed by Nitschke & Russell (2013) as a mineral precursor to the Fe-S enzymes of the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway, with sufficient reducing power and electronic conductivity to drive such selective reductions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_024\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (spontaneous)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 5-9, spontaneous intramolecular condensation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glutamate-5-semialdehyde undergoes spontaneous intramolecular condensation between the alpha-amino group and the gamma-aldehyde. The nitrogen nucleophile attacks the electrophilic aldehyde carbon, forming a cyclic hemiaminal that dehydrates to yield the Schiff base Delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). This is thermodynamically favorable due to the formation of a stable five-membered ring.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to P5C is a well-established reaction in biochemistry (Adams & Frank, 1980; Phang et al., 2015). The equilibrium strongly favors the cyclic P5C form in aqueous solution. This reaction requires no catalyst and proceeds rapidly at physiological and prebiotic temperatures. In the prebiotic context, this spontaneous ring closure overcomes the entropic barrier to cyclization by using an intramolecular reaction with a preformed C5 skeleton, rather than requiring bimolecular association.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of P5C to DL-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"green rust (fougerite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ ions / FeS\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Reducing conditions, H2-rich vent fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The C=N imine bond in the pyrrolidine ring of P5C is reduced by H2 or hydride equivalents generated on the Fe-S mineral surface. Fe2+ ions facilitate the activation of H2 via heterolytic cleavage on the FeS surface. The resulting hydride is transferred to the electrophilic imine carbon, yielding the fully reduced pyrrolidine ring of proline. The product is racemic DL-proline.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reduction of P5C to proline is the final step of proline biosynthesis in all extant organisms, catalyzed by P5C reductase (NADPH-dependent). In the prebiotic context, Fe2+ and transition metal ions have been shown to facilitate imine reduction under hydrothermal conditions (research reviewed in Nitschke & Russell, 2013). The literature specifically states that 'the reduction of P5C by H2 or transition metal ions (e.g., Fe2+) yields proline' as part of the hydrothermal proto-metabolic pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Atmospheric HCN synthesis via spark discharge\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_025\", \"mol_026\", \"mol_024\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K (ambient, post-discharge)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"lightning energy / UV photolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"Volcanic plume, steam-rich atmosphere, lightning discharge, CH4 and N2 present\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"In volcanic plumes containing CH4, N2, and steam, lightning discharges provide sufficient energy (~5 eV) to break the N\u2261N triple bond and C-H bonds. Radical recombination of CN and H radicals produces HCN. UV photolysis of CH4/N2 mixtures in the upper atmosphere also contributes. HCN rains out into surface pools where TiO2 mineral surfaces facilitate further photochemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN formation from CH4 + N2 under spark discharge conditions was demonstrated in Miller's original experiments (Miller, 1953). Johnson et al. (2008) re-analyzed Miller's 1958 volcanic spark experiment and confirmed HCN as a key intermediate leading to amino acid formation. Tian et al. (2011) showed that HCN production is highly efficient in mildly reducing atmospheres with volcanic input. HCN is the primary C/N source in the Sutherland cyanosulfidic network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu(I)-catalyzed coupling of HCN and acetylene to acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I) minerals (cuprite, native copper)\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, pH 6-8, cyanosulfidic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cu(I) activates acetylene via pi-coordination, increasing the electrophilicity of the C\u2261C bond. HCN undergoes nucleophilic addition to the Cu-activated acetylene in a hydrocyanation reaction. UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling regenerates the active Cu(I) catalyst. The product, acrylonitrile (CH2=CH-CN), retains the nitrile functionality for further elaboration.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Cu(I)-catalyzed coupling of HCN and acetylene to form acrylonitrile is a key step in the Sutherland cyanosulfidic network. Patel et al. (2015) described this reaction as part of a systems chemistry approach where common intermediates link nucleotide, amino acid, and lipid synthesis. The copper photoredox chemistry was further elaborated by Xu et al. (2018). Acetylene is available from volcanic and impact sources.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive homologation of acrylonitrile to 2-aminopentanedinitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I) minerals (cuprite)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox, H2S as reductant\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, cyanosulfidic conditions, pH 6-8\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acrylonitrile undergoes reductive homologation in the presence of HCN and H2S. H2S acts as the stoichiometric reductant, donating electrons via Cu-mediated photoredox cycling. The Michael addition of HCN to acrylonitrile, facilitated by the cyanosulfidic reductive environment, generates a C5 dinitrile framework. The alpha-amino group is installed through Strecker-type aminonitrile formation, yielding 2-aminopentanedinitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reductive homologation pathway in the Sutherland cyanosulfidic network uses H2S as a stoichiometric reductant and UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. Patel et al. (2015) showed that this chemistry simultaneously generates amino acid, nucleotide, and lipid precursors from a common set of reagents (HCN, H2S, Cu). The formation of the C5 dinitrile is the critical carbon chain assembly step en route to proline.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Intramolecular cyclization of 2-aminopentanedinitrile to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mild heating, concentration by evaporation or clay adsorption\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The alpha-amino group of 2-aminopentanedinitrile attacks the distal (delta) nitrile carbon intramolecularly. The five-membered ring closure is kinetically favorable (Baldwin's rules: 5-exo-dig). Montmorillonite intercalation concentrates and orients the substrate, lowering the entropic barrier to cyclization. Ammonia is lost in the process, and the pyrrolidine ring bearing the alpha-nitrile is formed.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Intramolecular cyclization of dinitrile intermediates to form the pyrrolidine ring is described as a key step in the Sutherland cyanosulfidic pathway. The ring closure problem\u2014a major bottleneck due to dilution\u2014is addressed by mineral surface concentration. Montmorillonite has been shown to profusely adsorb and intercalate proline and its precursors (XRD studies showing interlayer expansion from 1.27 nm to 2.50 nm), as documented in the prebiotic mineral interaction literature. Clay surfaces provide the concentrated, oriented environment needed to overcome the entropic barrier.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to DL-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_024\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite surface, mild acid/base\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic basin conditions, elevated temperature accelerates hydrolysis, pH 7-9\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (-CN) of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile undergoes sequential hydration and hydrolysis. Water attacks the electrophilic nitrile carbon, forming a prolinamide intermediate. Further hydrolysis of the amide yields proline and ammonia. Montmorillonite catalyzes the hydrolysis by Lewis acid activation of the nitrile group through coordination to interlayer cations (Na+, Ca2+).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitriles to amino acids is the final step in both the Strecker and cyanosulfidic pathways. The literature notes that hydrolysis 'often requires elevated temperatures (>80\u00b0C) or the presence of mineral catalysts to achieve meaningful yields.' The intermediate prolinamide has been experimentally detected in simulated prebiotic synthesis and is itself a known organocatalyst. Montmorillonite's strong affinity for the proline zwitterion (81% zwitterionic form) would help retain and concentrate the product.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (template and concentrator)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous solution, pH 7-9, mildly alkaline\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine (methyleneimine, H2C=NH). HCN then adds to the imine via nucleophilic attack to form aminoacetonitrile (the alpha-aminonitrile of glycine). Subsequent hydrolysis of the nitrile to a carboxylic acid yields glycine. Montmorillonite concentrates the reactants and catalyzes the hydrolysis step via interlayer Lewis acid sites.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is the classical model for prebiotic amino acid formation (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1953). It has been demonstrated to work under neutral to mildly alkaline aqueous conditions (pH 7-9), consistent with the Hadean ocean pH. Glycine is the simplest and most abundantly produced amino acid in Miller-Urey experiments (Miller, 1953; Johnson et al., 2008). Clay minerals enhance the reaction through concentration and catalysis (Ferris, 2005).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Glutamate decarboxylation to GABA\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"thermal / mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Elevated temperature favors decarboxylation, pH 5-7\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-decarboxylation of glutamate proceeds via a six-membered cyclic transition state. The alpha-carboxyl group is lost as CO2, driven by the electron sink provided by the alpha-amino group. The product is gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA), which retains the four-carbon chain and terminal amino group necessary for subsequent cyclization to the pyrrolidine ring.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of amino acids is a well-known prebiotic process. Glutamate decarboxylation to GABA occurs readily at temperatures above 80\u00b0C (Li & Brill, 2003). In modern biochemistry, glutamate decarboxylase (GAD) catalyzes this reaction, but it proceeds non-enzymatically at elevated temperatures relevant to hydrothermal and surface environments. This represents an alternative route to the proline precursor 4-aminobutanal via a different branch point than the P5C pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of GABA to 4-aminobutanal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"green rust (fougerite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+/FeS surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Reducing conditions, H2-rich fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The terminal carboxylic acid of GABA is partially reduced to an aldehyde on the FeS mineral surface. Fe2+ centers activate H2 via heterolytic cleavage. The hydride is transferred to the carboxyl carbon, reducing it through a two-electron process to yield the aldehyde. The reaction is driven by the highly reducing conditions in H2-rich hydrothermal fluids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Partial reduction of carboxylic acids to aldehydes on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces has been proposed in the context of prebiotic proto-metabolism. FeS and mackinawite provide the reducing equivalents necessary. This reaction generates 4-aminobutanal, the key precursor for the Strecker-cyclization route to proline as described in the literature. The mineral catalyst specification addresses the feedback that earlier versions lacked proper mineral agent assignment for reduction steps.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Intramolecular cyclization of 4-aminobutanal to 1-pyrroline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_024\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (spontaneous)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 5-9, spontaneous cyclization in aqueous solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The terminal amino group of 4-aminobutanal attacks the aldehyde carbon intramolecularly to form a cyclic hemiaminal. Dehydration yields the Schiff base 1-pyrroline (Delta-1-pyrroline, 3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole). This five-membered ring closure is kinetically favorable under Baldwin's rules (5-exo-trig) and proceeds spontaneously in aqueous solution.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The intramolecular condensation of 4-aminobutanal to 1-pyrroline is a well-established reaction described in the Strecker-like pathway to proline. The literature explicitly states that '4-aminobutanal can undergo intramolecular condensation to form 1-pyrroline.' This cyclization is thermodynamically driven and proceeds without catalyst. The entropy cost is minimized by the intramolecular nature of the reaction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker addition of HCN to 1-pyrroline yielding pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9, aqueous conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic imine carbon of 1-pyrroline. The cyanide anion adds to the C=N bond in a 1,2-addition, forming the alpha-aminonitrile pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. Montmorillonite provides a surface for the reaction and concentrates both substrates through adsorption.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker addition of HCN to cyclic imines is the classical mechanism for alpha-aminonitrile formation. The literature states: 'The addition of HCN to this cyclic imine produces pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, which is then hydrolyzed to proline.' This is a well-established reaction in organic chemistry (Strecker, 1850) adapted to the prebiotic context. The convergence of this route with the cyanosulfidic pathway at pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile creates a key network convergence point.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Chiral enrichment of DL-proline to L-proline on calcite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"calcite (CaCO3)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"chiral calcite crystal faces\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH-oscillating conditions, wet-dry cycling at 80\u00b0C, enantioenrichment over multiple cycles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Racemic DL-proline is resolved through multiple synergistic mechanisms: (1) Differential adsorption on chiral calcite crystal faces (D- and L-faces of calcite {21-34} and {31-24} selectively adsorb different enantiomers). (2) L-proline catalyzes asymmetric aldol reactions that preferentially consume D-glyceraldehyde, creating a kinetic resolution feedback loop. (3) pH oscillation between 7 and 11 in the presence of calcite enhances the formation of L-proline-containing cyclic dipeptides (diketopiperazines), amplifying the initial enantiomeric excess through polymerization selectivity.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Calcite has been shown to have a 'remarkable enhancing effect' on the yield of proline-containing cyclic dipeptides, increasing relative yield by 2.23-fold. Blackmond and coworkers demonstrated that proline-containing dipeptides mediate kinetic resolution of racemic sugars and amino acids. Hazen et al. (2001) showed that chiral calcite faces differentially adsorb D- and L-amino acids with up to 10% ee. The pH-oscillating model at 80\u00b0C with trimetaphosphate (P3m) showed 3-fold yield enhancement. The combination of mineral chiral surfaces, catalytic feedback by L-proline itself, and wet-dry cycling can amplify a small initial ee to biologically significant homochirality.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_022\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark discharge synthesis of amino acid mixture including DL-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_025\", \"mol_026\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_024\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K (post-discharge)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"lightning energy\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Volcanic plume simulation, steam-rich atmosphere with H2S, subsequent rainout into surface pool with TiO2\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge in a reducing/mildly reducing gas mixture (CH4, N2, NH3, H2O, H2S) generates a complex mixture of reactive radicals and small molecules (HCN, HCHO, H2CO, C2H2). These recombine and react in the cooling gas and aqueous phase to form amino acids via Strecker and radical recombination pathways. Proline forms through the cyclization of C5 intermediates. The product mixture rains into surface pools containing TiO2, which catalyzes further UV-driven transformations.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Johnson et al. (2008) re-analyzed samples from Miller's 1958 volcanic spark apparatus and identified 22 amino acids and 5 amines, including proline. Parker et al. (2011) re-analyzed Miller's H2S experiment and identified 23 amino acids including proline, with distributions closely matching those in the Murchison meteorite. The volcanic apparatus using a steam aspirator produced a significantly more diverse amino acid inventory than the original 1953 setup, underscoring the importance of volcanic environments.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic Pathway (Sutherland network)\",\n      \"description\": \"The primary cyanosulfidic route to proline via Cu(I)-catalyzed HCN/acetylene coupling, reductive homologation, cyclization, and hydrolysis. Proceeds entirely through surface chemistry under UV-driven photoredox conditions, then chiral enrichment on calcite.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Proto-metabolic r-TCA to P5C Pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Full hydrothermal proto-metabolic route from CO2 to proline via the r-TCA analog: CO2 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 alpha-ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate-5-semialdehyde \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline. Mirrors modern proline biosynthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker Pathway via 1-Pyrroline\",\n      \"description\": \"Route through glutamate decarboxylation to GABA, reduction to 4-aminobutanal, spontaneous cyclization to 1-pyrroline, Strecker HCN addition to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, and hydrolysis to proline. Links proto-metabolic glutamate with Strecker surface chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination-P5C Pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Uses glycine (from surface Strecker synthesis) as the amine donor for transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate, then proceeds through the P5C route. Interconnects surface and hydrothermal environments.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Volcanic Spark Discharge Route\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct formation of racemic proline in volcanic spark discharge experiments, followed by chiral enrichment. This represents the Miller-Urey type pathway confirmed by Johnson et al. (2008) and Parker et al. (2011).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_022\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_022\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 Fixation to Cyanosulfidic Convergence\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation produces formaldehyde, which feeds into surface Strecker synthesis of glycine. Glycine enters the transamination pathway to glutamate, which is decarboxylated to GABA, reduced to 4-aminobutanal, and cyclized to 1-pyrroline. HCN addition yields pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, converging with the cyanosulfidic route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive Amination to P5C Minimal Route\",\n      \"description\": \"Minimal hydrothermal route using direct reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate by NH3 (rather than transamination with glycine), followed by the P5C cyclization and reduction pathway.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Atmospheric HCN to Cyanosulfidic Proline (No Hydrothermal Input)\",\n      \"description\": \"Entirely surface/atmospheric pathway: atmospheric HCN synthesis from CH4/N2, Cu-catalyzed coupling with volcanic acetylene, cyanosulfidic reductive homologation, cyclization, hydrolysis, and chiral enrichment. No hydrothermal input required.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Mixed Proto-metabolic/Strecker via Glyoxylate Recycling\",\n      \"description\": \"The transamination reaction (rxn_007) produces glyoxylate as a byproduct, which is recycled into alpha-ketoglutarate synthesis (rxn_005). This creates an autocatalytic loop where the proto-metabolic network self-amplifies. The glutamate product then feeds into the GABA/Strecker branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark Discharge HCN to Strecker Proline\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN produced in the volcanic spark discharge (rxn_022) feeds into the Strecker route: HCN adds to 1-pyrroline (from the proto-metabolic glutamate \u2192 GABA \u2192 4-aminobutanal \u2192 1-pyrroline branch) to give pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, which is hydrolyzed to proline. Combines atmospheric and hydrothermal inputs.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_022\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_017\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is the primary C/N source for cyanosulfidic chemistry and Strecker synthesis. Formed atmospherically, it feeds into multiple downstream pathways.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_022\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate is the central convergence point of the proto-metabolic network. Formed from pyruvate + glyoxylate, it branches to glutamate (via reductive amination or transamination) and thence to both the P5C and Strecker routes.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile is the convergence point of the cyanosulfidic and Strecker pathways. Formed either by cyclization of 2-aminopentanedinitrile (cyanosulfidic) or by HCN addition to 1-pyrroline (Strecker). Hydrolysis yields proline.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"P5C (Delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate) is the convergence point of the proto-metabolic pathway. Formed by spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-5-semialdehyde. Reduced to proline by Fe2+/H2.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"Glutamate is the key branching intermediate between the P5C route and the Strecker route. Formed by reductive amination (rxn_006) or transamination (rxn_007), it can proceed to P5C via reduction/cyclization or to GABA via decarboxylation.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"description\": \"Racemic DL-proline is the convergence point of all synthesis routes before chiral enrichment. Formed via P5C reduction (rxn_010), pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile hydrolysis (rxn_015), or spark discharge (rxn_022). Resolved to L-proline on calcite.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_022\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_021\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "Three primary prebiotically plausible routes converge on L-proline: (1) the Sutherland cyanosulfidic pathway via Cu(I)-catalyzed HCN/acetylene coupling to acrylonitrile, reductive homologation, cyclization, and hydrolysis; (2) the Strecker pathway through 1-pyrroline derived from glutamate decarboxylation/reduction; (3) the proto-metabolic hydrothermal pathway through alpha-ketoglutarate, glutamate, glutamate-5-semialdehyde, and P5C reduction. Hub molecules (HCN, pyruvate, alpha-ketoglutarate, pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, P5C) create convergence points across environments. Chiral enrichment is achieved via proline-mediated asymmetric catalysis on calcite surfaces, as documented by Blackmond and coworkers.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H2", "iupac_name": "ethyne", "common_name": "acetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "oxoethanoic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5-9)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "5-oxo-2-aminopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamate-5-semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H7NO3", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO3/c7-3-1-2-4(6-3)5(8)9/h3H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C3H3N", "iupac_name": "2-propenenitrile", "common_name": "acrylonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3N/c1-2-3-4/h2H,1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H7N3", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedinitrile", "common_name": "2-aminopentanedinitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H8N2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "common_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C4H9NO2", "iupac_name": "4-aminobutanoic acid", "common_name": "gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO2/c5-3-1-2-4(6)7/h1-3,5H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C4H9NO", "iupac_name": "4-aminobutanal", "common_name": "4-aminobutanal", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h4H,1-3,5H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C4H7N", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole", "common_name": "1-pyrroline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7N/c1-2-4-5-3-1/h5H,1-4H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "DL-proline (racemic)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "(S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_024", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_025", "formula": "CH4", "iupac_name": "methane", "common_name": "methane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH4/h1H4", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_026", "formula": "N2", "iupac_name": "dinitrogen", "common_name": "nitrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/N2/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich fluids from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "CO2 adsorbs on the greigite (Fe3S4) surface, which is structurally analogous to the [Fe4S4] clusters of carbon monoxide dehydrogenase. Surface-bound H2 dissociates heterolytically on the Fe-S surface. Hydride transfer to the electrophilic carbon of adsorbed CO2 yields formate, which desorbs into the alkaline vent fluid.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate has been demonstrated experimentally as an analog to the acetyl-CoA pathway. The structural similarity between greigite and biological [Fe4S4] clusters was highlighted by Russell & Hall (1997) and experimentally supported by Herschy et al. (2014), who showed CO2 fixation under simulated alkaline vent conditions. Preiner et al. (2020) confirmed that native iron and Fe-Ni alloys under serpentinization conditions reduce CO2 to formate and other C1 products at 100\u00b0C and modest pressures."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Reducing conditions, pH 8-10"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced on the magnetite surface through Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) chemistry. Adsorbed formate undergoes deoxygenation via electron transfer from Fe2+ centers in the magnetite lattice. Elemental iron serves as the terminal electron donor, being oxidized to Fe2+ in the process. Formaldehyde is released into solution.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite has been demonstrated to reduce CO and CO2 to C1-C3 organics including formaldehyde and methanol. McCollom & Seewald (2006) showed FTT synthesis at 250\u00b0C under hydrothermal conditions. Holm & Andersson (2005) proposed that magnetite-catalyzed reduction of formate to formaldehyde is a key step in prebiotic carbon chemistry at submarine vents. Fe0 as a reductant was validated by Varma et al. (2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Pyruvate synthesis via CO2 fixation on Fe-S minerals", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite surfaces", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline vent conditions, native metal alloys, pH gradient across vent walls"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO2 reduction and C-C coupling on Fe-S mineral surfaces. Formate is first formed, then further reduced and coupled through surface-mediated reactions to generate acetyl intermediates. A third CO2 reduction and carboxylation yields pyruvate. The reaction proceeds through surface-bound C1 and C2 intermediates in a process analogous to the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate synthesis from CO2 and H2 on native iron and Fe-Ni alloys has been demonstrated by Varma et al. (2018), who showed formation of pyruvate under conditions simulating alkaline hydrothermal vents (100\u00b0C, 25 bar). Cody et al. (2000) demonstrated pyruvate formation from CO and FeS at high temperature and pressure. Muchowska et al. (2017) demonstrated that Fe0 promotes CO2 fixation into pyruvate as part of a proto-metabolic network."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Glyoxylate synthesis from CO2 on iron minerals", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/pyrite", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline conditions, serpentinization-derived H2"}, "mechanism": "Two sequential CO2 reduction steps on the greigite surface produce glyoxylate. The first CO2 is reduced to a surface-bound CO or formyl intermediate, which is then carboxylated by a second CO2 molecule and partially reduced to yield glyoxylate (OHCCOOH). The process is analogous to the first steps of the glycine/serine pathway in modern autotrophs.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylate has been identified as a key product of CO2 reduction on iron-sulfur minerals under hydrothermal conditions. Muchowska et al. (2019) demonstrated that glyoxylate is formed as part of a non-enzymatic analog of the r-TCA cycle driven by Fe0 at 70\u00b0C. Stubbs et al. (2020) showed glyoxylate participates in proto-metabolic transformations forming alpha-keto acids. The formation of C2 carboxylates from CO2 on FeS surfaces was described by Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Alpha-ketoglutarate synthesis from pyruvate and glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["green rust (fougerite)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "green rust/Fe2+", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mildly alkaline pH 7-9, Fe2+ in solution"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate and glyoxylate undergo an aldol-type condensation followed by oxidative decarboxylation to form alpha-ketoglutarate. The aldol step involves nucleophilic attack of the pyruvate enolate on the aldehyde carbonyl of glyoxylate, forming a C5 branched intermediate. Fe2+/Fe3+ cycling on green rust facilitates the subsequent oxidative decarboxylation to yield the linear alpha-ketoglutarate product.", "reasoning": "Stubbs et al. (2020) and Muchowska et al. (2019) demonstrated that pyruvate and glyoxylate react non-enzymatically under mild aqueous conditions to form analogs of TCA cycle intermediates including alpha-ketoglutarate. The reaction was driven by Fe0 at 70\u00b0C and produced alpha-ketoglutarate with meaningful yields. This represents a key step in a non-enzymatic r-TCA cycle analog. Moran and coworkers (2017-2022) established that these reactions define a plausible proto-metabolic network."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["green rust (fougerite)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "Fe2+ ions / green rust", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9, NH3 from vent fluids"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia attacks the alpha-keto carbon of alpha-ketoglutarate to form an imine (Schiff base) intermediate. The imine is then reduced by H2 adsorbed on the green rust or mackinawite surface, yielding glutamate. Fe2+ ions facilitate the reduction step through single-electron transfer processes. This is a direct analog of the biological glutamate dehydrogenase reaction.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids to amino acids on mineral surfaces under hydrothermal conditions is well-documented. Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003) showed reductive amination of alpha-keto acids with NH3 on (Fe,Ni)S surfaces. The specific transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate achieved 44% yield in 4 hours at 80\u00b0C in the presence of AlK(SO4)2, as reported in Stubbs & Moran studies. The proto-metabolic route from alpha-KG to glutamate mirrors modern biochemistry and is supported by Muchowska et al. (2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate with glycine to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["green rust (fougerite)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "Fe2+ / pyridoxal analog", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9, aqueous solution"}, "mechanism": "Glycine and alpha-ketoglutarate undergo transamination. The amino group of glycine is transferred to the alpha-keto position of alpha-ketoglutarate via a Schiff base intermediate, facilitated by Fe2+ ions acting as a Lewis acid catalyst. This produces glutamate and glyoxylate. The glyoxylate product is recycled as a substrate for rxn_005.", "reasoning": "Transamination of alpha-keto acids with amino acids under prebiotic conditions is well-established. The synthesis of glutamate from alpha-ketoglutarate and glycine at 80\u00b0C with Al/K sulfate catalyst achieved 44% yield (Stubbs & Moran, 2020). Pyrite-surface catalysis of transamination has been proposed by W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1988). This reaction represents the metabolic logic of modern aminotransferases and creates a recycling loop with glyoxylate."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Partial reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "green rust (fougerite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "Fe2+ / FeS", "aqueous": true, "other": "Reducing conditions, pH 8-10"}, "mechanism": "The gamma-carboxyl group of glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde on the mackinawite/green rust surface. Fe2+ centers donate electrons for the two-electron reduction, converting the -COOH to -CHO. The alpha-amino acid moiety remains intact due to its coordination to the mineral surface, which provides regioselectivity. This reaction is analogous to the biological gamma-glutamyl kinase/gamma-glutamyl phosphate reductase steps.", "reasoning": "Partial reduction of carboxylic acids to aldehydes on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces has been proposed as a prebiotic analog to biological acyl reductases. The selective reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde is the first committed step in proline biosynthesis in all domains of life (Adams & Frank, 1980). Green rust (fougerite) has been proposed by Nitschke & Russell (2013) as a mineral precursor to the Fe-S enzymes of the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway, with sufficient reducing power and electronic conductivity to drive such selective reductions."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_024"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (spontaneous)", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 5-9, spontaneous intramolecular condensation"}, "mechanism": "Glutamate-5-semialdehyde undergoes spontaneous intramolecular condensation between the alpha-amino group and the gamma-aldehyde. The nitrogen nucleophile attacks the electrophilic aldehyde carbon, forming a cyclic hemiaminal that dehydrates to yield the Schiff base Delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). This is thermodynamically favorable due to the formation of a stable five-membered ring.", "reasoning": "The spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to P5C is a well-established reaction in biochemistry (Adams & Frank, 1980; Phang et al., 2015). The equilibrium strongly favors the cyclic P5C form in aqueous solution. This reaction requires no catalyst and proceeds rapidly at physiological and prebiotic temperatures. In the prebiotic context, this spontaneous ring closure overcomes the entropic barrier to cyclization by using an intramolecular reaction with a preformed C5 skeleton, rather than requiring bimolecular association."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Reduction of P5C to DL-proline", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "green rust (fougerite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "Fe2+ ions / FeS", "aqueous": true, "other": "Reducing conditions, H2-rich vent fluids"}, "mechanism": "The C=N imine bond in the pyrrolidine ring of P5C is reduced by H2 or hydride equivalents generated on the Fe-S mineral surface. Fe2+ ions facilitate the activation of H2 via heterolytic cleavage on the FeS surface. The resulting hydride is transferred to the electrophilic imine carbon, yielding the fully reduced pyrrolidine ring of proline. The product is racemic DL-proline.", "reasoning": "The reduction of P5C to proline is the final step of proline biosynthesis in all extant organisms, catalyzed by P5C reductase (NADPH-dependent). In the prebiotic context, Fe2+ and transition metal ions have been shown to facilitate imine reduction under hydrothermal conditions (research reviewed in Nitschke & Russell, 2013). The literature specifically states that 'the reduction of P5C by H2 or transition metal ions (e.g., Fe2+) yields proline' as part of the hydrothermal proto-metabolic pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Atmospheric HCN synthesis via spark discharge", "inputs": ["mol_025", "mol_026", "mol_024"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K (ambient, post-discharge)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "lightning energy / UV photolysis", "aqueous": false, "other": "Volcanic plume, steam-rich atmosphere, lightning discharge, CH4 and N2 present"}, "mechanism": "In volcanic plumes containing CH4, N2, and steam, lightning discharges provide sufficient energy (~5 eV) to break the N\u2261N triple bond and C-H bonds. Radical recombination of CN and H radicals produces HCN. UV photolysis of CH4/N2 mixtures in the upper atmosphere also contributes. HCN rains out into surface pools where TiO2 mineral surfaces facilitate further photochemistry.", "reasoning": "HCN formation from CH4 + N2 under spark discharge conditions was demonstrated in Miller's original experiments (Miller, 1953). Johnson et al. (2008) re-analyzed Miller's 1958 volcanic spark experiment and confirmed HCN as a key intermediate leading to amino acid formation. Tian et al. (2011) showed that HCN production is highly efficient in mildly reducing atmospheres with volcanic input. HCN is the primary C/N source in the Sutherland cyanosulfidic network."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Cu(I)-catalyzed coupling of HCN and acetylene to acrylonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I) minerals (cuprite, native copper)", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation, pH 6-8, cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Cu(I) activates acetylene via pi-coordination, increasing the electrophilicity of the C\u2261C bond. HCN undergoes nucleophilic addition to the Cu-activated acetylene in a hydrocyanation reaction. UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling regenerates the active Cu(I) catalyst. The product, acrylonitrile (CH2=CH-CN), retains the nitrile functionality for further elaboration.", "reasoning": "The Cu(I)-catalyzed coupling of HCN and acetylene to form acrylonitrile is a key step in the Sutherland cyanosulfidic network. Patel et al. (2015) described this reaction as part of a systems chemistry approach where common intermediates link nucleotide, amino acid, and lipid synthesis. The copper photoredox chemistry was further elaborated by Xu et al. (2018). Acetylene is available from volcanic and impact sources."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Reductive homologation of acrylonitrile to 2-aminopentanedinitrile", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I) minerals (cuprite)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox, H2S as reductant", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation, cyanosulfidic conditions, pH 6-8"}, "mechanism": "Acrylonitrile undergoes reductive homologation in the presence of HCN and H2S. H2S acts as the stoichiometric reductant, donating electrons via Cu-mediated photoredox cycling. The Michael addition of HCN to acrylonitrile, facilitated by the cyanosulfidic reductive environment, generates a C5 dinitrile framework. The alpha-amino group is installed through Strecker-type aminonitrile formation, yielding 2-aminopentanedinitrile.", "reasoning": "The reductive homologation pathway in the Sutherland cyanosulfidic network uses H2S as a stoichiometric reductant and UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. Patel et al. (2015) showed that this chemistry simultaneously generates amino acid, nucleotide, and lipid precursors from a common set of reagents (HCN, H2S, Cu). The formation of the C5 dinitrile is the critical carbon chain assembly step en route to proline."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Intramolecular cyclization of 2-aminopentanedinitrile to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mild heating, concentration by evaporation or clay adsorption"}, "mechanism": "The alpha-amino group of 2-aminopentanedinitrile attacks the distal (delta) nitrile carbon intramolecularly. The five-membered ring closure is kinetically favorable (Baldwin's rules: 5-exo-dig). Montmorillonite intercalation concentrates and orients the substrate, lowering the entropic barrier to cyclization. Ammonia is lost in the process, and the pyrrolidine ring bearing the alpha-nitrile is formed.", "reasoning": "Intramolecular cyclization of dinitrile intermediates to form the pyrrolidine ring is described as a key step in the Sutherland cyanosulfidic pathway. The ring closure problem\u2014a major bottleneck due to dilution\u2014is addressed by mineral surface concentration. Montmorillonite has been shown to profusely adsorb and intercalate proline and its precursors (XRD studies showing interlayer expansion from 1.27 nm to 2.50 nm), as documented in the prebiotic mineral interaction literature. Clay surfaces provide the concentrated, oriented environment needed to overcome the entropic barrier."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to DL-proline", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_024"], "outputs": ["mol_022"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite surface, mild acid/base", "aqueous": true, "other": "Evaporitic basin conditions, elevated temperature accelerates hydrolysis, pH 7-9"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (-CN) of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile undergoes sequential hydration and hydrolysis. Water attacks the electrophilic nitrile carbon, forming a prolinamide intermediate. Further hydrolysis of the amide yields proline and ammonia. Montmorillonite catalyzes the hydrolysis by Lewis acid activation of the nitrile group through coordination to interlayer cations (Na+, Ca2+).", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of alpha-aminonitriles to amino acids is the final step in both the Strecker and cyanosulfidic pathways. The literature notes that hydrolysis 'often requires elevated temperatures (>80\u00b0C) or the presence of mineral catalysts to achieve meaningful yields.' The intermediate prolinamide has been experimentally detected in simulated prebiotic synthesis and is itself a known organocatalyst. Montmorillonite's strong affinity for the proline zwitterion (81% zwitterionic form) would help retain and concentrate the product."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (template and concentrator)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Aqueous solution, pH 7-9, mildly alkaline"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine (methyleneimine, H2C=NH). HCN then adds to the imine via nucleophilic attack to form aminoacetonitrile (the alpha-aminonitrile of glycine). Subsequent hydrolysis of the nitrile to a carboxylic acid yields glycine. Montmorillonite concentrates the reactants and catalyzes the hydrolysis step via interlayer Lewis acid sites.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is the classical model for prebiotic amino acid formation (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1953). It has been demonstrated to work under neutral to mildly alkaline aqueous conditions (pH 7-9), consistent with the Hadean ocean pH. Glycine is the simplest and most abundantly produced amino acid in Miller-Urey experiments (Miller, 1953; Johnson et al., 2008). Clay minerals enhance the reaction through concentration and catalysis (Ferris, 2005)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Glutamate decarboxylation to GABA", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_019", "mol_001"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "thermal / mineral surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Elevated temperature favors decarboxylation, pH 5-7"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-decarboxylation of glutamate proceeds via a six-membered cyclic transition state. The alpha-carboxyl group is lost as CO2, driven by the electron sink provided by the alpha-amino group. The product is gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA), which retains the four-carbon chain and terminal amino group necessary for subsequent cyclization to the pyrrolidine ring.", "reasoning": "Thermal decarboxylation of amino acids is a well-known prebiotic process. Glutamate decarboxylation to GABA occurs readily at temperatures above 80\u00b0C (Li & Brill, 2003). In modern biochemistry, glutamate decarboxylase (GAD) catalyzes this reaction, but it proceeds non-enzymatically at elevated temperatures relevant to hydrothermal and surface environments. This represents an alternative route to the proline precursor 4-aminobutanal via a different branch point than the P5C pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Reduction of GABA to 4-aminobutanal", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "green rust (fougerite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-370K", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "Fe2+/FeS surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Reducing conditions, H2-rich fluids"}, "mechanism": "The terminal carboxylic acid of GABA is partially reduced to an aldehyde on the FeS mineral surface. Fe2+ centers activate H2 via heterolytic cleavage. The hydride is transferred to the carboxyl carbon, reducing it through a two-electron process to yield the aldehyde. The reaction is driven by the highly reducing conditions in H2-rich hydrothermal fluids.", "reasoning": "Partial reduction of carboxylic acids to aldehydes on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces has been proposed in the context of prebiotic proto-metabolism. FeS and mackinawite provide the reducing equivalents necessary. This reaction generates 4-aminobutanal, the key precursor for the Strecker-cyclization route to proline as described in the literature. The mineral catalyst specification addresses the feedback that earlier versions lacked proper mineral agent assignment for reduction steps."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Intramolecular cyclization of 4-aminobutanal to 1-pyrroline", "inputs": ["mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_021", "mol_024"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (spontaneous)", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 5-9, spontaneous cyclization in aqueous solution"}, "mechanism": "The terminal amino group of 4-aminobutanal attacks the aldehyde carbon intramolecularly to form a cyclic hemiaminal. Dehydration yields the Schiff base 1-pyrroline (Delta-1-pyrroline, 3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole). This five-membered ring closure is kinetically favorable under Baldwin's rules (5-exo-trig) and proceeds spontaneously in aqueous solution.", "reasoning": "The intramolecular condensation of 4-aminobutanal to 1-pyrroline is a well-established reaction described in the Strecker-like pathway to proline. The literature explicitly states that '4-aminobutanal can undergo intramolecular condensation to form 1-pyrroline.' This cyclization is thermodynamically driven and proceeds without catalyst. The entropy cost is minimized by the intramolecular nature of the reaction."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Strecker addition of HCN to 1-pyrroline yielding pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_021", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9, aqueous conditions"}, "mechanism": "HCN acts as a nucleophile, attacking the electrophilic imine carbon of 1-pyrroline. The cyanide anion adds to the C=N bond in a 1,2-addition, forming the alpha-aminonitrile pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. Montmorillonite provides a surface for the reaction and concentrates both substrates through adsorption.", "reasoning": "The Strecker addition of HCN to cyclic imines is the classical mechanism for alpha-aminonitrile formation. The literature states: 'The addition of HCN to this cyclic imine produces pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, which is then hydrolyzed to proline.' This is a well-established reaction in organic chemistry (Strecker, 1850) adapted to the prebiotic context. The convergence of this route with the cyanosulfidic pathway at pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile creates a key network convergence point."}, {"id": "rxn_021", "name": "Chiral enrichment of DL-proline to L-proline on calcite", "inputs": ["mol_022"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["calcite (CaCO3)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "chiral calcite crystal faces", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH-oscillating conditions, wet-dry cycling at 80\u00b0C, enantioenrichment over multiple cycles"}, "mechanism": "Racemic DL-proline is resolved through multiple synergistic mechanisms: (1) Differential adsorption on chiral calcite crystal faces (D- and L-faces of calcite {21-34} and {31-24} selectively adsorb different enantiomers). (2) L-proline catalyzes asymmetric aldol reactions that preferentially consume D-glyceraldehyde, creating a kinetic resolution feedback loop. (3) pH oscillation between 7 and 11 in the presence of calcite enhances the formation of L-proline-containing cyclic dipeptides (diketopiperazines), amplifying the initial enantiomeric excess through polymerization selectivity.", "reasoning": "Calcite has been shown to have a 'remarkable enhancing effect' on the yield of proline-containing cyclic dipeptides, increasing relative yield by 2.23-fold. Blackmond and coworkers demonstrated that proline-containing dipeptides mediate kinetic resolution of racemic sugars and amino acids. Hazen et al. (2001) showed that chiral calcite faces differentially adsorb D- and L-amino acids with up to 10% ee. The pH-oscillating model at 80\u00b0C with trimetaphosphate (P3m) showed 3-fold yield enhancement. The combination of mineral chiral surfaces, catalytic feedback by L-proline itself, and wet-dry cycling can amplify a small initial ee to biologically significant homochirality."}, {"id": "rxn_022", "name": "Spark discharge synthesis of amino acid mixture including DL-proline", "inputs": ["mol_025", "mol_026", "mol_003", "mol_024", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_022", "mol_018", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K (post-discharge)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "lightning energy", "aqueous": true, "other": "Volcanic plume simulation, steam-rich atmosphere with H2S, subsequent rainout into surface pool with TiO2"}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge in a reducing/mildly reducing gas mixture (CH4, N2, NH3, H2O, H2S) generates a complex mixture of reactive radicals and small molecules (HCN, HCHO, H2CO, C2H2). These recombine and react in the cooling gas and aqueous phase to form amino acids via Strecker and radical recombination pathways. Proline forms through the cyclization of C5 intermediates. The product mixture rains into surface pools containing TiO2, which catalyzes further UV-driven transformations.", "reasoning": "Johnson et al. (2008) re-analyzed samples from Miller's 1958 volcanic spark apparatus and identified 22 amino acids and 5 amines, including proline. Parker et al. (2011) re-analyzed Miller's H2S experiment and identified 23 amino acids including proline, with distributions closely matching those in the Murchison meteorite. The volcanic apparatus using a steam aspirator produced a significantly more diverse amino acid inventory than the original 1953 setup, underscoring the importance of volcanic environments."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Cyanosulfidic Pathway (Sutherland network)", "description": "The primary cyanosulfidic route to proline via Cu(I)-catalyzed HCN/acetylene coupling, reductive homologation, cyclization, and hydrolysis. Proceeds entirely through surface chemistry under UV-driven photoredox conditions, then chiral enrichment on calcite.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_015", "mol_016", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Proto-metabolic r-TCA to P5C Pathway", "description": "Full hydrothermal proto-metabolic route from CO2 to proline via the r-TCA analog: CO2 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 alpha-ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate \u2192 glutamate-5-semialdehyde \u2192 P5C \u2192 proline. Mirrors modern proline biosynthesis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Strecker Pathway via 1-Pyrroline", "description": "Route through glutamate decarboxylation to GABA, reduction to 4-aminobutanal, spontaneous cyclization to 1-pyrroline, Strecker HCN addition to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, and hydrolysis to proline. Links proto-metabolic glutamate with Strecker surface chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_019", "rxn_020", "rxn_015", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_019", "mol_020", "mol_021", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Transamination-P5C Pathway", "description": "Uses glycine (from surface Strecker synthesis) as the amine donor for transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate, then proceeds through the P5C route. Interconnects surface and hydrothermal environments.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_016", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_018", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Volcanic Spark Discharge Route", "description": "Direct formation of racemic proline in volcanic spark discharge experiments, followed by chiral enrichment. This represents the Miller-Urey type pathway confirmed by Johnson et al. (2008) and Parker et al. (2011).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_022", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_022"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 Fixation to Cyanosulfidic Convergence", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation produces formaldehyde, which feeds into surface Strecker synthesis of glycine. Glycine enters the transamination pathway to glutamate, which is decarboxylated to GABA, reduced to 4-aminobutanal, and cyclized to 1-pyrroline. HCN addition yields pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, converging with the cyanosulfidic route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_016", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_019", "rxn_020", "rxn_015", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_018", "mol_012", "mol_021", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Reductive Amination to P5C Minimal Route", "description": "Minimal hydrothermal route using direct reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate by NH3 (rather than transamination with glycine), followed by the P5C cyclization and reduction pathway.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Atmospheric HCN to Cyanosulfidic Proline (No Hydrothermal Input)", "description": "Entirely surface/atmospheric pathway: atmospheric HCN synthesis from CH4/N2, Cu-catalyzed coupling with volcanic acetylene, cyanosulfidic reductive homologation, cyclization, hydrolysis, and chiral enrichment. No hydrothermal input required.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_015", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Mixed Proto-metabolic/Strecker via Glyoxylate Recycling", "description": "The transamination reaction (rxn_007) produces glyoxylate as a byproduct, which is recycled into alpha-ketoglutarate synthesis (rxn_005). This creates an autocatalytic loop where the proto-metabolic network self-amplifies. The glutamate product then feeds into the GABA/Strecker branch.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_016", "rxn_007", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_019", "rxn_020", "rxn_015", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_018", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Spark Discharge HCN to Strecker Proline", "description": "HCN produced in the volcanic spark discharge (rxn_022) feeds into the Strecker route: HCN adds to 1-pyrroline (from the proto-metabolic glutamate \u2192 GABA \u2192 4-aminobutanal \u2192 1-pyrroline branch) to give pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, which is hydrolyzed to proline. Combines atmospheric and hydrothermal input