nder aqueous conditions, (3) the chiral enrichment step (rxn_021) is too vaguely specified\u2014calcite alone does not convert racemic proline to L-proline without additional mechanisms, and (4) the 'Biochemical' label on rxn_009, rxn_017, and rxn_019 is somewhat misleading since these are spontaneous chemical reactions that could occur in any aqueous environment. The literature alignment is outstanding\u2014all major routes, intermediates, and environmental conditions described in the research findings are represented. The network should be approved with the caveat that rxn_008 and rxn_018 represent genuine chemical challenges that need experimental validation.\",\n    \"approved\": true,\n    \"hub_quality\": 0.92,\n    \"convergence_quality\": 0.88\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_011": 0.9, "rxn_012": 0.85, "rxn_013": 0.8, "rxn_014": 0.8, "rxn_015": 0.8, "rxn_021": 0.7}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.82, "pathway_coherence": 0.9, "environmental_progression": 0.78, "target_achievement": 0.82, "overall_confidence": 0.84, "feedback": "This pathway faithfully reproduces the Sutherland cyanosulfidic route through acrylonitrile, reductive homologation, cyclization to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, and hydrolysis. It is the most directly literature-supported route. The Cu(I)-catalyzed coupling (rxn_012) is well-documented. The weakest link is the final chiral enrichment step (rxn_021), which is described abstractly\u2014calcite-mediated enantioenrichment likely requires additional co-catalysts or wet-dry cycling for significant ee values. The pathway remains entirely in the Surface environment, which is justified for cyanosulfidic chemistry but misses the Hydrothermal connection.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_021"], "suggestions": ["Elaborate chiral enrichment mechanism\u2014specify whether crystallization-induced deracemization, Viedma ripening, or kinetic resolution by proline-dipeptides is i