016": 0.9, "rxn_007": 0.85, "rxn_008": 0.55, "rxn_009": 0.9, "rxn_010": 0.75, "rxn_021": 0.7}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.76, "pathway_coherence": 0.83, "environmental_progression": 0.85, "target_achievement": 0.78, "overall_confidence": 0.8, "feedback": "This mixed pathway combines proto-metabolic and Strecker chemistry with glyoxylate recycling. The recycling of glyoxylate from the transamination step (rxn_007 produces glyoxylate) back into the r-TCA analog (rxn_005) is an elegant catalytic cycle that enhances network coherence. The environmental integration is strong. Still bottlenecked by rxn_008.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_002"], "suggestions": ["Explicitly diagram the glyoxylate catalytic cycle to show the autocatalytic nature of this network"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_011": 0.9, "rxn_001": 0.9, "rxn_002": 0.7, "rxn_016": 0.9, "rxn_003": 0.78, "rxn_004": 0.7, "rxn_005": 0.85, "rxn_007": 0.85, "rxn_017": 0.7, "rxn_018": 0.5, "rxn_019": 0.85, "rxn_020": 0.85, "rxn_015": 0.8, "rxn_021": 0.7}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.72, "pathway_coherence": 0.78, "environmental_progression": 0.82, "target_achievement": 0.75, "overall_confidence": 0.76, "feedback": "This long pathway integrates atmospheric HCN, hydrothermal proto-metabolism, and the Strecker addition to 1-pyrroline. It provides the most comprehensive environmental journey but at the cost of including the problematic GABA reduction step (rxn_018). The 11-step length and the inclusion of two weak reactions (rxn_018, rxn_002) reduce overall confidence.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_018", "rxn_002"], "suggestions": ["Find an alternative route to 4-aminobutanal that avoids GABA reduction"]}], "best_pathway_id": "P1", "overall_confidence": 0.85, "network_feedback": "This is an exceptionally well-designed synthesis network for L-proline that demonstrates deep engagement with the prebiotic chemistry literature. The network successfully integrates three major paradigms\u2014cyanosulfidic systems chemistry (Sutherland), proto-metabolic r-TCA analogs (Stubbs/Moran), and classical Strecker/Miller-Urey chemistry\u2014into a coherent multi-environment framework. The 26-molecule, 22-reaction, 10-pathway architecture provides genuine convergence through 5 well-chosen hub molecules (HCN, pyruvate, alpha-ketoglutarate, pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, P5C). The strongest aspects are: (1) the faithful reproduction of the Sutherland cyanosulfidic pathway, (2) the glyoxylate recycling catalytic cycle connecting transamination products back to r-TCA inputs, (3) the convergence at pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile from both cyanosulfidic and Strecker routes, and (4) the explicit treatment of chirality via calcite-mediated enrichment (Blackmond). Key weaknesses include: (1) the partial reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde (rxn_008) lacks a convincing prebiotic mechanism, (2) the GABA to 4-aminobutanal reduction (rxn_018) is thermodynamically unfavorable under aqueous conditions, (3) the chiral enrichment step (rxn_021) is too vaguely specified\u2014calcite alone does not convert racemic proline to L-proline without additional mechanisms, and (4) the 'Biochemical' label on rxn_009, rxn_017, and rxn_019 is somewhat misleading since these are spontaneous chemical reactions that could occur in any aqueous environment. The literature alignment is outstanding\u2014all major routes, intermediates, and environmental conditions described in the research findings are represented. The network should be approved with the caveat that rxn_008 and rxn_018 represent genuine chemical challenges that need experimental validation.", "approved": true, "hub_quality": 0.92, "convergence_quality": 0.88}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 282224.85995292664, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T07:34:20.886419", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: L-Proline\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof L-Proline. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis and Geochemical Evolution of L-Proline: A Systems Chemistry PerspectiveThe emergence of the proteinogenic amino acids on the early Earth represents one of the most significant transitions in chemical evolution, marking the shift from abiotic geochemistry to the organized molecular systems characteristic of life. Among the twenty standard amino acids, L-proline holds a position of unique structural and functional significance. As the only proteinogenic amino acid containing a secondary amine\u2014where the side chain is covalently bonded to the nitrogen atom to form a five-membered pyrrolidine ring\u2014proline imposes severe conformational constraints on the polypeptide backbone. These constraints are essential for the formation of alpha-helices, beta-turns, and the triple-helical structure of collagen, the most abundant protein in mammalian systems. Furthermore, the secondary amine structure of proline allows it to function as a potent organocatalyst in prebiotic environments, facilitating asymmetric C-C bond formation and enantioenrichment of other critical building blocks like sugars and primary amino acids. Understanding the prebiotic synthesis of L-proline requires an integrated analysis of atmospheric chemistry, hydrothermal geochemistry, mineral-surface interactions, and the systems-level pathways that characterize cyanosulfidic protometabolism.Structural and Functional Significance of Proline in Prebiotic ContextsThe chemical architecture of proline, defined by its cyclic $C_{5}H_{9}NO_{2}$ structure, differs fundamentally from the linear $\\alpha$-amino acids. In most amino acids, the $\\alpha$-amino group is primary, allowing for a high degree of rotational freedom around the $N-C_{\\alpha}$ ($\\phi$) and $C_{\\alpha}-C$ ($\\psi$) bonds. In proline, the nitrogen atom is part of a pyrrolidine ring, which restricts the $\\phi$ angle to approximately $-65^{\\circ}$. This rigidity makes proline a \"helix breaker\" or a \"turn inducer\" in proteins, providing the structural templates necessary for complex folding. In a prebiotic sense, this structural rigidity would have been instrumental in the transition from random peptide oligomers to functional, folded proto-enzymes.Beyond its structural role, proline and its precursors, such as prolinamide, exhibit intrinsic catalytic activity. Proline has been demonstrated to catalyze the aldol condensation of glyceraldehyde to form pentose sugars, a reaction central to the emergence of the \"RNA World\". Its ability to adopt both cis and trans conformations in significant abundance\u2014rooted in the similar steric hindrance of these two forms in the pyrrolidine ring\u2014allows it to regulate multiple biological and prebiotic pathways through isomerization. This unique chemical behavior suggests that proline was not merely a passive building block but an active participant in the chemical selection processes of the Hadean Earth.Known Prebiotic Synthesis Routes for L-ProlineThe synthesis of proline under prebiotic conditions has been investigated through several distinct chemical frameworks, ranging from high-energy atmospheric simulations to low-energy systems chemistry and hydrothermal geochemistry.Cyanosulfidic Systems Chemistry and Reductive HomologationThe most robust and prebiotically plausible pathway for proline synthesis discovered in recent years is the cyanosulfidic network developed by the Sutherland group. This approach utilizes a restricted set of simple starting materials\u2014hydrogen cyanide ($HCN$), hydrogen sulfide ($H_{2}S$), and water ($H_{2}O$)\u2014to simultaneously generate the precursors for nucleotides, amino acids, and lipids.The synthesis of proline within this network involves the reductive homologation of $HCN$ and its derivatives. A critical step in the assembly of the five-carbon skeleton of proline is the copper-catalyzed cross-coupling of hydrogen cyanide  and acetylene. This reaction generates acrylonitrile , which then undergoes further reductive homologation. In this \"systems chemistry\" framework, the reaction is driven by ultraviolet (UV) radiation and catalyzed by photoredox cycling between $Cu(I)$ and $Cu(II)$.The pathway proceeds through several key stages:Cyanosulfidic Reduction: Reductive homologation of acrylonitrile in the presence of $H_{2}S$ as a reductant leads to the formation of 2-aminopentanedinitrile.Cyclization and Hydrolysis: The five-carbon dinitrile intermediate undergoes intramolecular cyclization to form pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile.Final Synthesis: The hydrolysis of the nitrile group in pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile yields the final L-proline molecule.This route is highly efficient because it leverages the same reagents and conditions required for the synthesis of pyrimidine ribonucleotides and lipid precursors, suggesting that all three cellular subsystems could have emerged from a shared chemical history.Precursor MoleculeRole in PathwayEnvironmental DriversSourceHydrogen Cyanide ($HCN$)Primary C/N sourceUV light, LightningAcetylene ($C_{2}H_{2}$)Carbon chain extensionVolcanic/Impact eventsHydrogen Sulfide ($H_{2}S$)Stoichiometric reductantVolcanic emissionsAcrylonitrileC3 intermediate$Cu(I)$ catalysisPyrrolidine-2-carbonitrileImmediate alpha-aminonitrileAqueous hydrolysisThe Strecker Synthesis PathwayThe Strecker synthesis is the classical model for prebiotic amino acid formation, involving the reaction of an aldehyde or ketone with ammonia and hydrogen cyanide. While the synthesis of simple amino acids like glycine and alanine from formaldehyde and acetaldehyde is well-established, the synthesis of proline via this route requires a more complex, functionalized four-carbon aldehyde.The proposed Strecker-like mechanism for proline involves the formation of a cyclic imine intermediate. Specifically, 4-aminobutanal can undergo intramolecular condensation to form 1-pyrroline. The addition of $HCN$ to this cyclic imine produces pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, which is then hydrolyzed to proline. This pathway relies on the availability of 4-substituted aldehydes, which could have been formed through the condensation of smaller aldehydes (e.g., glycolaldehyde) or through the reductive homologation of $HCN$.Experimental evidence supports the feasibility of the Strecker reaction in aqueous solution under neutral to mildly alkaline conditions (pH 7\u20139), which are consistent with the estimated pH of the Hadean oceans. However, the hydrolysis of the nitrile intermediate represents a significant kinetic bottleneck, often requiring elevated temperatures ($>80^{\\circ}C$) or the presence of mineral catalysts to achieve meaningful yields.Hydrothermal and Proto-Metabolic PathwaysIn contrast to the \"genetics-first\" scenarios that emphasize atmospheric and UV-driven chemistry, \"metabolism-first\" hypotheses propose that proline was synthesized within the geochemical reactors of alkaline hydrothermal vents. These environments provide persistent gradients of pH, temperature, and redox potential, facilitating the emergence of a rudimentary proto-metabolism.Recent studies by Stubbs and Moran (2020-2022) have demonstrated that alpha-keto acids, such as pyruvate and glyoxylate, can react under mild aqueous conditions to produce analogs of the reductive tricarboxylic acid (r-TCA) cycle without the need for complex enzymes. Specifically, the reaction between pyruvate and glyoxylate can generate $\\alpha$-ketoglutarate, the biological precursor to glutamate and proline.The hydrothermal synthesis of proline from these intermediates follows a path congruent with modern biochemistry:Transamination: $\\alpha$-ketoglutarate reacts with an amine donor (such as glycine or ammonia) to form glutamate.Cyclization: Glutamate-5-semialdehyde, an intermediate formed by the partial reduction of glutamate, spontaneously cyclizes to form $\\Delta^1$-pyrroline-5-carboxylate ($P5C$).Reduction: The reduction of $P5C$ by $H_{2}$ or transition metal ions (e.g., $Fe^{2+}$) yields proline.This \"autotrophic\" pathway is particularly appealing because it aligns with the core biosynthetic logic found in all kingdoms of life, suggesting a seamless transition from geochemistry to biochemistry.Key Intermediates and PrecursorsThe path to L-proline is characterized by a set of critical intermediates that serve as nodal points in prebiotic chemical networks. These molecules bridge the gap between simple inorganic gases and the complex cyclic structure of the amino acid.Small Molecule PrecursorsHydrogen Cyanide ($HCN$): The primary source of the $\\alpha$-carbon and nitrogen. In the Sutherland pathway, $HCN$ is the sole source for all carbon and nitrogen atoms in the resulting amino acids.Acetylene ($C_{2}H_{2}$): Provides the additional carbon atoms for the side chain through $Cu(I)$-catalyzed coupling.Pyruvate and Glyoxylate: Key alpha-keto acids that serve as the foundation for the r-TCA cycle analogs and the synthesis of $\\alpha$-ketoglutarate.Hydrogen Sulfide ($H_{2}S$): Acts as the stoichiometric reductant in cyanosulfidic pathways and is essential for the formation of sulfur-containing amino acids, which may have co-precipitated with proline.Branch Point IntermediatesPyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile: The immediate alpha-aminonitrile precursor. Its formation marks the closure of the pyrrolidine ring and the final stage before hydrolysis to proline.$\\Delta^1$-Pyrroline-5-carboxylate ($P5C$): A central intermediate in the hydrothermal/biochemical route. $P5C$ is a branch point for the synthesis of proline, glutamate, and arginine.Prolinamide: A stable amide that has been detected in simulated prebiotic synthesis. Prolinamide serves as a key precursor for the formation of proline-containing cyclic dipeptides under wet-dry cycling conditions.Environmental Conditions for SynthesisThe prebiotic synthesis of proline is highly sensitive to the local geochemical environment. The diverse conditions required for chain extension, cyclization, and hydrolysis suggest that different stages of the synthesis may have occurred in distinct, yet interconnected, geological niches.Hydrothermal Vent EnvironmentsSubmarine alkaline hydrothermal vents (AHVs) are characterized by the circulation of hot, alkaline fluids through a porous mineral matrix.Temperature and Pressure: Temperatures in these systems typically range from $40^{\\circ}C$ to $100^{\\circ}C$, with high hydrostatic pressures. These conditions are favorable for the condensation of small organic acids and the transamination of alpha-keto acids.Redox Gradients: The presence of $H_{2}$-rich fluids and electrochemical gradients across Fe(Ni)S mineral barriers facilitates the reduction of $CO_{2}$ and the formation of amino acid precursors.pH Gradients: The transition from alkaline vent fluids (pH 9\u201311) to the more acidic Hadean ocean (pH 5\u20136) provides the thermodynamic drive for many protometabolic reactions.Surface and Volcanic EnvironmentsSubaerial environments, such as volcanic hot springs and tidal pools, provide unique drivers that are absent in the deep sea.UV Radiation: Essential for the photoredox chemistry of the cyanosulfidic pathway. UV light drives the $Cu(I)/Cu(II)$ cycle and the reductive homologation of nitriles.Wet-Dry Cycles: Evaporative pools on volcanic islands or tidal flats undergo periodic dehydration. These cycles drive the formation of peptide bonds and the cyclization of prolinamide into cyclic dipeptides.Atmospheric Energy: Lightning discharges in steam-rich volcanic plumes provide the energy for the synthesis of complex organic mixtures, as demonstrated in the re-analysis of Miller's 1958 volcanic spark experiment.EnvironmentPrimary Energy SourceKey Reaction MechanismAdvantage for ProlineAlkaline VentRedox/pH GradientsReductive aminationStable supply of $H_{2}$Volcanic PlumeLightningSpark dischargeDiverse AA inventoryTidal PoolUV/EvaporationPhotoredox/Wet-dry cyclesRing closure, PolymerizationEvaporitic BasinThermal energyConcentrationNitrile hydrolysisMineral Catalysts and Surface InteractionsMineral surfaces are not passive observers in prebiotic chemistry; they act as catalysts, templates, and protective scaffolds. Proline's interaction with minerals is particularly interesting due to its secondary amine structure and cyclic side chain.Iron-Sulfur Minerals: Greigite and PyriteIron-sulfur minerals like greigite ($Fe_{3}S_{4}$) and pyrite ($FeS_{2}$) are thought to be the predecessors of the iron-sulfur clusters in modern metalloenzymes.Catalytic Activity: These minerals facilitate the reduction of $CO_{2}$ and $N_{2}$, providing the building blocks for amino acids.Protective Role: Pyrite has been shown to have a strong affinity for the anionic form of proline. Interestingly, the presence of adsorbed proline prevents the oxidation of the pyrite surface, suggesting a mutual stabilizing effect between the organic and mineral phases.Clay Minerals: MontmorilloniteMontmorillonite, a common prebiotic silicate, exhibits the highest molecular affinity for proline among several minerals of prebiotic interest.Intercalation: XRD studies have confirmed that proline profusely intercalates into the interlayer spaces of montmorillonite, significantly increasing the interlayer distance (from 1.27 nm to 2.50 nm).Concentration: Montmorillonite's strong affinity for the zwitterionic form of proline (81%) allows it to concentrate the amino acid from dilute aqueous solutions, potentially facilitating polymerization.Other Catalysts: Calcite and Green RustCalcite: In pH-oscillating models, calcite has been shown to have a \"remarkable enhancing effect\" on the yield of proline-containing cyclic dipeptides, increasing the relative yield by 2.23-fold.Green Rust (Fougerite): Mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxides like green rust exhibit substantial electronic conductivity and have been proposed as mineral precursors to the enzymes involved in the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.Experimental Evidence and Yield AnalysisThe synthesis of proline has been confirmed in a variety of laboratory simulations, from the iconic spark discharge experiments of the 1950s to modern systems chemistry assays.Re-analysis of the Miller-Urey ExperimentsThe original 1953 Miller-Urey experiment, which utilized a reducing atmosphere of $CH_{4}, NH_{3}, H_{2},$ and $H_{2}O$, primarily detected simple amino acids like glycine and alanine using paper chromatography. However, re-analyses of archived samples using state-of-the-art HPLC-ToF-MS techniques have drastically expanded the inventory.The 1958 Volcanic Experiment: In a re-analysis by Johnson et al. (2008), samples from Miller's \"volcanic\" apparatus\u2014which used a steam aspirator to simulate volcanic eruptions\u2014revealed a much higher diversity of products, including 22 amino acids and 5 amines. Proline was positively identified in these residues.The 1958 $H_{2}S$ Experiment: Parker et al. (2011) re-analyzed samples where $H_{2}S$ was added to the gas mixture. This experiment produced 23 amino acids, with proline being confirmed. The relative abundance of amino acids in these $H_{2}S$ experiments correlates closely with the distributions found in carbonaceous meteorites like Murchison.Quantitative Yields in Modern SimulationsModern experimental setups provide more precise yield and selectivity data.pH-Oscillating Models: In the synthesis of $Cyclo\\text{-}Pro\\text{-}Pro$ from prolinamide at $80^{\\circ}C$, the highest yields were achieved by oscillating the pH between 7 and 11. The addition of a prebiotic activator, trimetaphosphate ($P_{3}m$), resulted in a three-fold increase in yield.Sutherland Pathways: While the Sutherland group emphasizes the efficiency and co-production of building blocks rather than just yield, their photoredox cycles provide high conversion rates of nitriles to amino acids under mild conditions ($35^{\\circ}C$, neutral pH).Transamination Yields: The synthesis of glutamate (a proline precursor) from $\\alpha$-ketoglutarate and glycine achieved a 44% yield in 4 hours at $80^{\\circ}C$ in the presence of $AlK(SO_{4})_{2}$.Proline and the Emergence of HomochiralityA fundamental question in prebiotic geochemistry is how the biological preference for L-amino acids emerged from racemic mixtures. L-Proline appears to be a critical actor in this transition through its role as a chiral organocatalyst.Kinetic Resolution Mediated by ProlineResearch by the Blackmond and Sutherland groups has shown that proline-containing dipeptides can mediate the kinetic resolution of racemic mixtures.Sugar Enantioenrichment: L-proline (as an N-terminal residue in dipeptides like $Pro\\text{-}Val$) reacts preferentially with L-glyceraldehyde to form an Amadori rearrangement byproduct. This selective reaction removes L-glyceraldehyde from the system, leaving behind an excess of the proteinogenic D-glyceraldehyde.Amino Acid Enantioenrichment: In transamination reactions involving pyridoxal/pyridoxamine co-catalysts, $LL\\text{-}dipeptides$ (including those with N-terminal proline) have been shown to effect the kinetic resolution of racemic amino acids, preferentially leaving behind the L-enantiomer.This suggest that even a small initial enantioenrichment of proline\u2014perhaps through chiral mineral surfaces like calcite or the circular polarization of light\u2014could have been amplified through catalytic feedback loops, leading to the homochirality observed in modern biology.Open Questions and Unresolved ChallengesDespite the identification of several plausible pathways, the prebiotic synthesis of L-proline still faces significant scientific challenges.The Ring Closure ProblemThe synthesis of proline requires the efficient formation of a five-membered ring. While intramolecular cyclization of 4-aminobutanal is possible, the concentrations of such precursors in a primordial ocean would likely have been extremely low. The entropic barrier to ring closure in dilute solution is a major bottleneck. Researchers are currently investigating whether mineral surfaces or the concentrated environment of evaporative basins could have overcome this barrier.Hydrolysis vs. DecompositionThe hydrolysis of $\\alpha$-aminonitriles to amino acids is a key step in the Strecker and cyanosulfidic pathways. However, the same conditions that favor hydrolysis (high temperature, alkaline pH) can also lead to the decomposition of the nitrile or the resulting amino acid. Finding a \"geochemical sweet spot\" where hydrolysis is fast but decomposition is minimized remains a challenge.The Continuity of MetabolismThere is a significant gap between the abiotic synthesis of proline and its integration into the earliest self-sustaining metabolic cycles. While Stubbs and Moran have shown that r-TCA cycle analogs can emerge abiotically, the transition to the enzyme-controlled $P5C\\text{-}proline$ cycle seen in modern cells is not fully understood. The \"Alanine World\" hypothesis suggests that glycine and proline may have been remnants of an even earlier, simpler genetic code (the GC-phase), which was subsequently expanded.Analytical Sensitivity and ContaminationDetecting proline in archived samples or meteorites requires extremely sensitive analytical techniques (limits of detection in the sub-femtomole range). Discriminating between abiotically synthesized proline and modern microbial contamination\u2014which is predominantly L-proline\u2014is a persistent challenge. The racemic nature of the major amino acids in Miller's archived samples is a strong indicator of their abiotic origin, but the search for a definitive chiral bias in extraterrestrial proline continues.Conclusions and Implications for Synthesis DesignThe prebiotic synthesis of L-proline is best understood as a multi-stage process occurring within a dynamic, interconnected geochemical landscape. The most robust models point to the synergy between three key scenarios:Atmospheric Synthesis: High-energy volcanic plumes provided the initial inventory of amino acids and nitriles.Systems Chemistry: Cyanosulfidic networks allowed for the efficient homologation and cyclization of these precursors under UV-driven photoredox conditions.Hydrothermal Maturation: Alkaline vents provided the stable conditions and mineral catalysts (Fe-S minerals, green rust) for the emergence of proto-metabolic pathways that align with modern biosynthesis.The unique conformational rigidity and catalytic potential of proline suggest that it played a foundational role in the origin of life, not only as a building block for the first folded peptides but also as a primary driver for the emergence of biological homochirality. Future research into the synthesis of proline must focus on the \"flow chemistry\" of the early Earth\u2014how molecules moved between these disparate environments\u2014and the role of mineral catalysts in facilitating the critical ring-closure and hydrolysis steps that define this essential amino acid.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.85\n- Feedback: This is a well-designed and comprehensive synthesis network for L-proline that closely follows the current state of prebiotic chemistry literature. The three major routes (cyanosulfidic, Strecker, proto-metabolic) are all discussed in the literature and are appropriately represented. Key strengths: (1) Excellent network topology with 23 molecules, 20 reactions, 10 pathways, and 6 convergence points. (2) Hub molecules are well-chosen and properly connected, with HCN and formaldehyde serving as critical distribution nodes. (3) The convergence at pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile from two independent routes is chemically meaningful. (4) Strong alignment with Sutherland cyanosulfidic work and Stubbs/Moran proto-metabolic studies. (5) The environmental flow from hydrothermal CO2 fixation through surface chemistry to biochemical maturation is logical and well-justified. Key weaknesses: (1) rxn_008 (formaldehyde + NH3 \u2192 HCN) is chemically questionable\u2014this is not a standard or well-supported HCN production mechanism. (2) rxn_014 (glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde + NH3 \u2192 4-aminobutanal) is oversimplified and needs decomposition into elementary steps. (3) rxn_018 (selective reduction of glutamate to semialdehyde) lacks a specified mineral catalyst. (4) The L-specificity of proline is not addressed by any reaction in the network\u2014all routes produce racemic proline. The literature discusses proline's role in chiral amplification but this is not incorporated. (5) Some surface reactions lack mineral catalyst specifications. Despite these issues, the network represents a high-quality synthesis plan with multiple viable pathways to the target.\n- Issues: ['Extends P1 with hydrothermal CO2 fixation origins, which is conceptually appealing and gives the full Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow. However, rxn_008 (formaldehyde + NH3 \u2192 HCN via UV dehydration) is the weakest link. HCN is typically formed from N2/NH3 + CH4 under high energy conditions (lightning, UV photolysis of CH4/N2 mixtures), not from formaldehyde dehydration with ammonia. Formaldehyde + NH3 more plausibly yields aminomethanol or formamide, not HCN directly.', 'The Strecker-like pathway through 4-aminobutanal and 1-pyrroline is a legitimate route discussed in the literature. The Strecker addition of HCN to 1-pyrroline (rxn_016) is well-established. However, rxn_014 is oversimplified\u2014the conversion of glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde + NH3 to 4-aminobutanal involves at least two distinct steps (aldol extension to a C4 aldehyde, then reductive amination), and the selectivity for the correct regiochemistry is not guaranteed. The formose reaction (rxn_013) lacks a specified mineral catalyst. Environmental flow is only Surface \u2192 Biochemical.', 'Full hydrothermal-to-surface Strecker pathway provides good environmental flow. Inherits the weaknesses of P3 (rxn_014 oversimplification) plus the questionable formate-to-formaldehyde reduction (rxn_002). The pathway logic is sound but several individual steps need refinement.', 'The longest pathway spanning all three environments. The full chain from CO2 to glycine (via hydrothermal \u2192 surface Strecker) to proline (via transamination and proto-metabolic route) is conceptually elegant and represents true systems chemistry. However, it inherits the problematic rxn_008 and is vulnerable to cumulative yield losses across 11 steps. The convergent use of glycine as both a product and a reagent in transamination is a nice feature.', 'Combines the weaknesses of P2 (rxn_008) and P3 (rxn_014). While the environmental flow is good, two problematic reactions in the same pathway significantly undermine confidence.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.85\n- Feedback: This is an exceptionally well-designed synthesis network for L-proline that demonstrates deep engagement with the prebiotic chemistry literature. The network successfully integrates three major paradigms\u2014cyanosulfidic systems chemistry (Sutherland), proto-metabolic r-TCA analogs (Stubbs/Moran), and classical Strecker/Miller-Urey chemistry\u2014into a coherent multi-environment framework. The 26-molecule, 22-reaction, 10-pathway architecture provides genuine convergence through 5 well-chosen hub molecules (HCN, pyruvate, alpha-ketoglutarate, pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, P5C). The strongest aspects are: (1) the faithful reproduction of the Sutherland cyanosulfidic pathway, (2) the glyoxylate recycling catalytic cycle connecting transamination products back to r-TCA inputs, (3) the convergence at pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile from both cyanosulfidic and Strecker routes, and (4) the explicit treatment of chirality via calcite-mediated enrichment (Blackmond). Key weaknesses include: (1) the partial reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde (rxn_008) lacks a convincing prebiotic mechanism, (2) the GABA to 4-aminobutanal reduction (rxn_018) is thermodynamically unfavorable under aqueous conditions, (3) the chiral enrichment step (rxn_021) is too vaguely specified\u2014calcite alone does not convert racemic proline to L-proline without additional mechanisms, and (4) the 'Biochemical' label on rxn_009, rxn_017, and rxn_019 is somewhat misleading since these are spontaneous chemical reactions that could occur in any aqueous environment. The literature alignment is outstanding\u2014all major routes, intermediates, and environmental conditions described in the research findings are represented. The network should be approved with the caveat that rxn_008 and rxn_018 represent genuine chemical challenges that need experimental validation.\n- Issues: ['This long pathway goes through glutamate \u2192 GABA \u2192 4-aminobutanal \u2192 1-pyrroline \u2192 pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile \u2192 proline. While the Strecker addition of HCN to 1-pyrroline (rxn_020) is well-documented in the literature, the reduction of GABA to 4-aminobutanal (rxn_018) is the most chemically problematic step in the entire network. Reducing a carboxylic acid to an aldehyde under aqueous conditions without specialized reagents is very difficult. The 10-step length also raises concerns about overall yield. The convergence with the cyanosulfidic pathway at pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile (mol_017) is a nice touch.', 'This pathway uses glycine as the transamination donor (rxn_007), connecting the Strecker-derived glycine to the proto-metabolic pathway. The transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate with glycine is supported by experimental evidence (44% yield at 80\u00b0C cited in literature). The glyoxylate recycling aspect (produced as a byproduct of transamination) is elegant and adds network coherence. Still suffers from the rxn_008 weakness. The 11-step length is long but the convergence is well-designed.', \"This minimal 2-step route via spark discharge (rxn_022) is supported by Johnson et al. (2008) re-analysis of Miller's volcanic apparatus and Parker et al. (2011) H2S experiments. However, rxn_022 is essentially a black box\u2014it produces multiple products in low yields without mechanistic specificity. The direct production of DL-proline in spark discharge experiments, while confirmed analytically, occurs at trace levels. This pathway lacks the mechanistic depth expected of a proper synthesis network. The environmental progression is also minimal\u2014it stays in Surface with no Hydrothermal input.\", 'This is the minimal version of P2, using reductive amination directly rather than transamination. It is more parsimonious and avoids the need for glycine as an amine donor. The direct reductive amination (rxn_006) with NH3 and H2 on iron minerals is well-supported. Still limited by the rxn_008 bottleneck.', 'This long pathway integrates atmospheric HCN, hydrothermal proto-metabolism, and the Strecker addition to 1-pyrroline. It provides the most comprehensive environmental journey but at the cost of including the problematic GABA reduction step (rxn_018). The 11-step length and the inclusion of two weak reactions (rxn_018, rxn_002) reduce overall confidence.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Proline\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"Multi-environment synthesis network for L-proline integrating three established paradigms: (1) Sutherland cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry producing pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile via reductive homologation of HCN and acetylene; (2) proto-metabolic hydrothermal r-TCA cycle analog producing alpha-ketoglutarate, then glutamate, glutamate-5-semialdehyde, and P5C following the biological biosynthetic logic (Stubbs & Moran); (3) Strecker-type chemistry via 1-pyrroline intermediate. Hub molecules (HCN, pyruvate, alpha-ketoglutarate, pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, P5C) create convergence points. Glutamate-5-semialdehyde serves as a critical branch point feeding both the P5C reduction route and the Strecker route via thermal decarboxylation to 4-aminobutanal. Chiral enrichment via calcite-mediated differential adsorption and proline-catalyzed amplification (Blackmond). Environmental flow: Hydrothermal CO2 fixation \u2192 Surface cyanosulfidic/Strecker chemistry \u2192 Biochemical assembly and chiral selection.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethyne\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHO2-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"oxoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate-5-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H7NO3/c7-3-1-2-4(6-3)5(8)9/h3H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H3N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-propenenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H3N/c1-2-3-4/h2H,1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7N3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedinitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-aminopentanedinitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-aminobutanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"4-aminobutanal\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h4H,1-3,5H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole\",\n      \"common_name\": \"1-pyrroline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7N/c1-2-4-5-3-1/h5H,1-4H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DL-proline (racemic)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_024\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-proline\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_025\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"prolinamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10N2O/c6-5(8)4-2-1-3-7-4/h4,7H,1-3H2,(H2,6,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline vent fluid, pH 9-11, H2-rich serpentinization fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 adsorbs onto the greigite surface, which is structurally analogous to biological [Fe4S4] clusters. H2 dissociatively adsorbs on the mineral, providing hydride equivalents that reduce CO2 to formate via a surface-bound formate intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is one of the most well-established hydrothermal prebiotic reactions. Preiner et al. (2020) demonstrated native iron and Fe-Ni alloys reduce CO2 to formate, pyruvate, and acetate under alkaline hydrothermal conditions. Roldan et al. (2015) showed greigite electrochemically reduces CO2 to formate at low overpotentials, mimicking the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type reduction of formate to formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-470K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"FTT conditions in subseafloor hydrothermal systems\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced on magnetite surfaces via Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) hydrogenation. The carboxylate is activated on the oxide surface and reduced stepwise through a surface-bound formyl species to formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"McCollom & Seewald (2007) and He et al. (2019) demonstrated FTT synthesis produces formaldehyde and other oxygenated C1 species from CO/formate + H2 on magnetite under hydrothermal conditions. Magnetite provides both catalytic surface and reducing equivalents.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to pyruvate on Fe minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and native iron\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 9-11, alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Multi-step reduction of CO2 via sequential C1 additions on iron mineral surfaces. Formate and CO intermediates undergo carbonyl insertion and hydrogenation steps to build up to the C3 alpha-keto acid pyruvate. Native iron provides strong reducing potential.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2017) demonstrated the synthesis of pyruvate from CO2 and H2 on iron-containing minerals under mild aqueous conditions. Preiner et al. (2020) showed that native iron and Ni-Fe alloys in alkaline aqueous conditions at 100\u00b0C generate pyruvate alongside formate and acetate from CO2 and H2. This represents a prebiotically plausible carbon fixation pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyoxylate-pyruvate aldol condensation to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-380K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9, mild aqueous conditions, Fe2+ in solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol-type condensation between pyruvate and glyoxylate proceeds through a mineral-surface-mediated enolization of pyruvate, followed by nucleophilic addition to glyoxylate. Subsequent decarboxylation of the initial C5 beta-keto diacid intermediate yields alpha-ketoglutarate. The reaction is analogous to steps of the non-enzymatic r-TCA cycle.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Stubbs et al. (2020) demonstrated that pyruvate and glyoxylate react under mild aqueous conditions to form alpha-ketoglutarate through an aldol-decarboxylation sequence, recapitulating key r-TCA cycle steps without enzymes. Moran and colleagues (Muchowska et al., 2019) showed that Fe2+ and other simple metal ions catalyze an 11-reaction network including this transformation. FeS mineral surfaces facilitate the enolization step.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"green rust (fougerite)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-380K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"green rust (mixed-valence Fe oxyhydroxide)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 8-10, H2-rich, NH4+ available from hydrothermal fluid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia attacks the carbonyl carbon of alpha-ketoglutarate to form a carbinolamine, which dehydrates to an imine (Schiff base). The imine is then reduced by H2 activated on the green rust surface, yielding glutamate. Green rust provides both the mineral template and electronic conductivity for hydride transfer.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Barge et al. (2019) demonstrated reductive amination of alpha-keto acids in the presence of ammonia and mixed-valence iron minerals under alkaline hydrothermal conditions. The literature review explicitly states that alpha-ketoglutarate reacts with an amine donor to form glutamate as a step congruent with modern biochemistry. Green rust (fougerite) has been proposed as a mineral precursor to Fe-S enzymes involved in the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate with glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350K (80\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"AlK(SO4)2 or pyrite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"pH 7-9, 4 hours reaction time, 44% yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycine donates its amino group to alpha-ketoglutarate via a pyridoxal-independent transamination. The reaction proceeds through a geminal diamine intermediate or direct amine transfer facilitated by the metal ion catalyst. Glycine is converted to glyoxylate, creating a catalytic recycling loop.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature explicitly states: 'The synthesis of glutamate from alpha-ketoglutarate and glycine achieved a 44% yield in 4 hours at 80\u00b0C in the presence of AlK(SO4)2.' This is a key step in the proto-metabolic pathway. Transamination reactions between alpha-keto acids and amino acids are documented under mild prebiotic conditions (Muchowska et al., 2019). The glyoxylate byproduct feeds back into rxn_004, creating an autocatalytic loop.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Partial reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"green rust (fougerite)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"green rust, Fe2+ ions\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"H2-rich reducing environment, moderately alkaline pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The terminal carboxylic acid of glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde on the green rust surface. The mixed-valence iron mineral activates H2 as a hydride source. The reaction is regioselective because the alpha-carboxylate is stabilized by chelation with the amino group and the mineral surface, leaving the distal gamma-carboxylate exposed for reduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This partial reduction mirrors the biological glutamate-5-semialdehyde dehydrogenase reaction. While this specific prebiotic transformation remains experimentally challenging\u2014acknowledged as an open question in the literature\u2014green rust (fougerite) provides the electronic conductivity and mixed-valence iron centers needed for selective 2-electron reduction. Nitschke & Russell (2013) proposed that green rust minerals could mediate such selective reductions at alkaline vents. The research notes that Fe2+ and transition metal ions facilitate the reduction of P5C, implying the reverse direction is also accessible under more reducing conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to P5C\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Spontaneous intramolecular condensation, pH 5-9\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The alpha-amino group of glutamate-5-semialdehyde attacks the gamma-aldehyde intramolecularly, forming a cyclic carbinolamine that dehydrates to give the Schiff base delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). This is a thermodynamically favorable intramolecular condensation driven by the entropic advantage of five-membered ring formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature explicitly states: 'Glutamate-5-semialdehyde, an intermediate formed by the partial reduction of glutamate, spontaneously cyclizes to form delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C).' This is a well-established spontaneous reaction in both biochemistry and prebiotic chemistry, requiring no catalyst. The five-membered ring formation is kinetically and thermodynamically favored (Baldwin's rules: 5-exo-trig cyclization).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduction of P5C to DL-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm to moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ ions in solution\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Reducing environment with available H2 or Fe2+ as electron donor\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The C=N imine bond of P5C is reduced by H2 activated by dissolved Fe2+ ions or by direct hydride transfer from Fe2+-mediated H2 heterolysis. The reduction yields the saturated pyrrolidine ring of proline. This produces a racemic mixture (DL-proline).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature states: 'The reduction of P5C by H2 or transition metal ions (e.g., Fe2+) yields proline.' This final reduction step mirrors the biological pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase reaction. Under the reducing conditions of the Hadean Earth, with abundant dissolved Fe2+ and H2 from serpentinization, this reduction is thermodynamically favorable.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Copper-catalyzed HCN-acetylene coupling to acrylonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I)/Cu(II) minerals (cuprite/tenorite)\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, cyanosulfidic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cu(I) activates acetylene by coordination, enabling nucleophilic addition of cyanide to form acrylonitrile (2-propenenitrile). UV light drives the Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycle, regenerating the active Cu(I) species. The reaction proceeds through a vinyl-copper intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Sutherland group established that copper-catalyzed cross-coupling of HCN and acetylene generates acrylonitrile as a key C3 building block in the cyanosulfidic network. The literature states: 'A critical step in the assembly of the five-carbon skeleton of proline is the copper-catalyzed cross-coupling of hydrogen cyanide and acetylene. This reaction generates acrylonitrile, which then undergoes further reductive homologation.' UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling is the energy source (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic reductive homologation to 2-aminopentanedinitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I)/Cu(II) minerals\", \"stibnite (Sb2S3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) photoredox, H2S as stoichiometric reductant\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, mildly alkaline pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acrylonitrile undergoes reductive homologation with HCN in the presence of H2S as the stoichiometric reductant. H2S reduces the cyanide adduct through a thiocyanate intermediate, extending the carbon chain. The process involves: (1) conjugate addition of HCN to acrylonitrile to give a C4 dinitrile, (2) further reductive cyanide addition driven by UV/Cu cycling, (3) reductive amination at the alpha-position to yield the five-carbon 2-aminopentanedinitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Sutherland cyanosulfidic pathway uses reductive homologation of HCN derivatives with H2S as the reductant to build up carbon skeletons. The literature states: 'Reductive homologation of acrylonitrile in the presence of H2S as a reductant leads to the formation of 2-aminopentanedinitrile.' This is part of the network that simultaneously produces nucleotide, amino acid, and lipid precursors (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Intramolecular cyclization of 2-aminopentanedinitrile to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-360K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pool; concentration drives ring closure\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The free amino group attacks one of the terminal nitrile carbons intramolecularly, forming a five-membered pyrrolidine ring with loss of NH3 or via an amidine intermediate. Montmorillonite clay concentrates the substrate by intercalation and provides an acidic surface that activates the nitrile toward nucleophilic attack. Wet-dry cycling increases the effective concentration.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile as the immediate alpha-aminonitrile precursor formed by intramolecular cyclization of the dinitrile intermediate. The ring closure problem is noted as a key challenge: 'The entropic barrier to ring closure in dilute solution is a major bottleneck. Researchers are currently investigating whether mineral surfaces or the concentrated environment of evaporative basins could have overcome this barrier.' Montmorillonite has the highest molecular affinity for proline among minerals of prebiotic interest and its interlayer spaces provide a confined environment facilitating cyclization.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to prolinamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_025\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (acid catalysis in interlayer)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Neutral to mildly alkaline pH, partial hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile undergoes partial hydrolysis on the montmorillonite surface. Water attacks the electrophilic nitrile carbon, forming an iminol intermediate that tautomerizes to the amide (prolinamide). The clay surface provides Br\u00f8nsted acid sites that activate the nitrile toward nucleophilic addition of water.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies prolinamide as 'a stable amide that has been detected in simulated prebiotic synthesis' and states it 'serves as a key precursor for the formation of proline-containing cyclic dipeptides under wet-dry cycling conditions.' The stepwise hydrolysis nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid is well-established, with the amide being a kinetically accessible intermediate. Montmorillonite's high affinity for proline and its derivatives facilitates this transformation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of prolinamide to DL-proline via pH oscillation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_025\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"calcite (CaCO3)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"340-360K (80\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"calcite, pH oscillation between 7 and 11\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycles, evaporitic pool with calcite shores\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The amide bond of prolinamide is hydrolyzed to the free carboxylic acid under oscillating pH conditions. At high pH, hydroxide attacks the amide carbonyl; the return to neutral pH drives the equilibrium toward the free acid. Calcite dissolution and reprecipitation provides the pH oscillation. The elevated temperature (80\u00b0C) accelerates the hydrolysis kinetics.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature states that 'In the synthesis of Cyclo-Pro-Pro from prolinamide at 80\u00b0C, the highest yields were achieved by oscillating the pH between 7 and 11.' Calcite has 'a remarkable enhancing effect' on the yield of proline-related products, increasing relative yield by 2.23-fold. pH oscillation models driven by calcite dissolution/precipitation cycles are prebiotically plausible in evaporitic settings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to DL-proline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, mildly alkaline pH\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Prolonged heating in evaporitic basin, >80\u00b0C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complete hydrolysis of the nitrile group through the amide intermediate to the carboxylic acid under sustained heating. At elevated temperature and mildly alkaline pH, the hydrolysis proceeds through both the amide and direct pathways. Montmorillonite provides acid-base catalytic sites and concentrates the substrate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature states that 'the hydrolysis of the nitrile intermediate represents a significant kinetic bottleneck, often requiring elevated temperatures (>80\u00b0C) or the presence of mineral catalysts to achieve meaningful yields.' Direct complete hydrolysis (nitrile \u2192 acid) is the net transformation of rxn_013 + rxn_014 and is achievable with sufficient time and temperature. Montmorillonite provides the necessary catalytic surface.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Neutral to mildly alkaline pH (7-9)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Classic Strecker synthesis: (1) formaldehyde condenses with ammonia to form an imine (methylenimine), (2) HCN adds to the imine to form aminoacetonitrile (alpha-aminonitrile), (3) hydrolysis of the nitrile yields glycine. Montmorillonite concentrates the reactants and catalyzes the hydrolysis step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is described in the literature as 'the classical model for prebiotic amino acid formation, involving the reaction of an aldehyde or ketone with ammonia and hydrogen cyanide.' The synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde by this route is one of the most well-established prebiotic reactions (Miller, 1957; Strecker, 1850). Montmorillonite catalysis of amino acid formation is well-documented.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose reaction: formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ca(OH)2 / borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline conditions, borate stabilization of intermediates\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde self-condensation via the formose reaction. Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo an umpolung aldol condensation: one serves as the nucleophilic enolate equivalent (activated by base) and the other as the electrophilic aldehyde. Borate minerals complex with the product glycolaldehyde, stabilizing it against further uncontrolled polymerization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction producing sugars from formaldehyde is a well-established prebiotic pathway. The literature mentions 'Formose Reaction: n H2CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)2 or borate).' Borate minerals are critical for stabilizing sugars and preventing tar formation (Ricardo et al., 2004). Glycolaldehyde is the simplest sugar and serves as a key intermediate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to 4-aminobutanal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface, Fe2+ ions\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Elevated temperature favors decarboxylation over cyclization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-amino acid decarboxylation of glutamate-5-semialdehyde releases CO2 and produces 4-aminobutanal. The decarboxylation is facilitated by the alpha-amino group acting as an electron sink (analogous to PLP-dependent decarboxylation). At temperatures >100\u00b0C, the decarboxylation rate can compete with the intramolecular cyclization to P5C. Pyrite surface Lewis acid sites activate the carboxylate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of alpha-amino acids is well-documented under hydrothermal conditions (Li & Brill, 2003). Glutamate-5-semialdehyde possesses an alpha-amino acid moiety susceptible to decarboxylation. This creates a critical branch point in the network: at lower temperatures G5SA cyclizes to P5C (rxn_008), while at higher hydrothermal temperatures it decarboxylates to 4-aminobutanal, which feeds the Strecker pathway. This connection between the proto-metabolic and Strecker routes is a novel but chemically sound prediction.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Intramolecular cyclization of 4-aminobutanal to 1-pyrroline\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Spontaneous in aqueous solution at neutral to mildly acidic pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The primary amine of 4-aminobutanal attacks the aldehyde carbon intramolecularly, forming a cyclic hemiaminal that dehydrates to give 1-pyrroline (3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole). This is a thermodynamically favorable 5-exo-trig cyclization following Baldwin's rules.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature explicitly describes this reaction: '4-aminobutanal can undergo intramolecular condensation to form 1-pyrroline.' This is a well-known spontaneous reaction in organic chemistry. The five-membered ring formation is both kinetically and thermodynamically favorable. No catalyst is required.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_020\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker addition of HCN to 1-pyrroline forming pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Neutral to mildly alkaline pH, evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (from HCN) to the electrophilic C=N of 1-pyrroline (cyclic imine). The cyanide attacks the iminium carbon, forming the alpha-aminonitrile pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. This is a standard Strecker-type addition to a cyclic imine. Montmorillonite concentrates both reactants.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature describes this as a key step: 'The addition of HCN to this cyclic imine produces pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, which is then hydrolyzed to proline.' The Strecker addition to cyclic imines is well-established in prebiotic chemistry. This creates the second convergence point at pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile (also formed by the cyanosulfidic route, rxn_012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_021\",\n      \"name\": \"Enantiomeric enrichment of DL-proline to L-proline on calcite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_024\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"calcite chiral crystal faces, proline-catalyzed amplification\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Chiral calcite (2-1-4) and (0-1-4) faces selectively adsorb D- and L-enantiomers respectively; subsequent proline-catalyzed feedback amplifies initial ee\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two-stage chiral enrichment: (1) Differential adsorption\u2014DL-proline solution contacts calcite crystal faces that are inherently chiral. The (2-1-4) and (0-1-4) faces of calcite selectively adsorb one enantiomer, creating a solution enriched in the other. (2) Catalytic amplification\u2014the enantiomerically enriched proline catalyzes asymmetric aldol reactions (e.g., with glyceraldehyde), creating chiral products that feed back to further enrich L-proline through kinetic resolution in transamination reactions mediated by proline-containing dipeptides.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature extensively discusses proline's role in homochirality: 'L-proline (as an N-terminal residue in dipeptides like Pro-Val) reacts preferentially with L-glyceraldehyde' (Blackmond and Sutherland groups). 'Even a small initial enantioenrichment of proline\u2014perhaps through chiral mineral surfaces like calcite\u2014could have been amplified through catalytic feedback loops, leading to the homochirality observed in modern biology.' Hazen et al. (2001) demonstrated that calcite crystal faces show enantioselective adsorption of amino acids. The amplification mechanism via proline-catalyzed aldol reactions and kinetic resolution is documented by Blackmond (2004, 2010).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_022\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite, FeS\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is reduced to formate on greigite, then further reduced and carboxylated to form glyoxylate (oxoacetate). This two-step process involves the formation of a surface-bound CO/formyl species from formate, followed by carboxylation with a second CO2 molecule.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyoxylate is a central metabolite in the non-enzymatic r-TCA cycle. Muchowska et al. (2019) and Stubbs et al. (2020) include glyoxylate as a key intermediate produced from CO2 reduction on iron minerals. While the direct formation of glyoxylate from CO2 requires more complex surface chemistry than formate formation, it is a necessary component of the proto-metabolic network. The alkaline hydrothermal environment provides the thermodynamic driving force.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathway (direct hydrolysis)\",\n      \"description\": \"The primary cyanosulfidic route following Sutherland's systems chemistry. HCN and acetylene (from volcanic emissions) are coupled via Cu-catalyzed photoredox to form acrylonitrile, which is reductively homologated with H2S to 2-aminopentanedinitrile. Intramolecular cyclization on montmorillonite yields pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, which is directly hydrolyzed to DL-proline, then enantiomerically enriched to L-proline on calcite.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic via Prolinamide Intermediate\",\n      \"description\": \"A variant of P1 where pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile is partially hydrolyzed to prolinamide, then further hydrolyzed to proline under pH-oscillating conditions with calcite catalysis. This route is slower but achieves higher selectivity.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_025\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Proto-metabolic Reductive Amination Pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Full hydrothermal proto-metabolic route: CO2 is fixed to pyruvate and glyoxylate, which condense to alpha-ketoglutarate (r-TCA analog). Reductive amination yields glutamate, which is partially reduced to G5SA, cyclizes to P5C, and is reduced to proline. This pathway mirrors modern biochemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_022\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Proto-metabolic Transamination Pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Similar to P3 but uses glycine (from surface Strecker synthesis) as the amino donor instead of ammonia. This pathway demonstrates the essential Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Hydrothermal interconnection.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_022\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker Pathway via 1-Pyrroline (from G5SA decarboxylation)\",\n      \"description\": \"A hybrid pathway where hydrothermal proto-metabolism produces glutamate-5-semialdehyde, which undergoes thermal decarboxylation (instead of cyclization to P5C) to yield 4-aminobutanal. This spontaneously cyclizes to 1-pyrroline, which undergoes Strecker HCN addition to form pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, converging with the cyanosulfidic route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_022\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker-1-Pyrroline via Transamination Branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Variant of P5 using glycine-mediated transamination (rxn_006) instead of reductive amination (rxn_005) to form glutamate. Demonstrates the redundancy of amino group sources.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_022\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_021\", \"mol_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Full Hydrothermal-to-Surface CO2 Fixation \u2192 Glycine \u2192 Transamination\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete environmental trajectory: hydrothermal CO2 fixation produces formate and formaldehyde, which are transported to surface pools where Strecker synthesis produces glycine. Glycine returns to hydrothermal environment for transamination with alpha-ketoglutarate, producing glutamate that proceeds through P5C to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_022\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde Hub to Glycolaldehyde Route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde, then surface formose reaction to glycolaldehyde, which serves as a hub for further chemistry. Glycolaldehyde feeds into the broader prebiotic network. Combined with Strecker and proto-metabolic pathways for proline via glycine transamination route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_022\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_020\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic to Strecker Convergence at Pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile\",\n      \"description\": \"Demonstrates the convergence of the cyanosulfidic and Strecker-1-pyrroline routes at pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. Takes the proto-metabolic route to G5SA, decarboxylates to 4-aminobutanal, forms 1-pyrroline, adds HCN (Strecker), and then follows the prolinamide hydrolysis branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_022\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_020\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_022\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_025\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyoxylate Recycling Autocatalytic Loop\",\n      \"description\": \"Demonstrates the autocatalytic nature of the proto-metabolic network. Glyoxylate produced as a byproduct of the transamination (rxn_006) feeds back into the pyruvate-glyoxylate condensation (rxn_004), creating a self-amplifying cycle. Each turn of the cycle produces one glutamate equivalent that proceeds to proline.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_022\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_016\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_019\", \"mol_016\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN is a primary carbon/nitrogen source feeding into multiple routes: cyanosulfidic acrylonitrile formation, Strecker glycine synthesis, and Strecker addition to 1-pyrroline. Derived from volcanic/atmospheric processes.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is the central C3 alpha-keto acid hub. Produced by hydrothermal CO2 fixation, it feeds into the r-TCA-like condensation with glyoxylate to build the C5 skeleton of proline precursors.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate is the critical C5 convergence point. Formed from pyruvate + glyoxylate condensation, it is the branch point for both reductive amination (with NH3) and transamination (with glycine) to glutamate. All proto-metabolic routes pass through this hub.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile is the major convergence point where the cyanosulfidic pathway (rxn_012) and the Strecker-1-pyrroline pathway (rxn_020) meet. It is the immediate alpha-aminonitrile precursor to proline.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_020\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"description\": \"Delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) is the central branch point of the proto-metabolic pathway. Formed by spontaneous cyclization of G5SA, it is reduced directly to proline. P5C is also a biological branch point to glutamate and arginine.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"description\": \"Glutamate-5-semialdehyde is a critical branch point: at moderate temperatures it cyclizes to P5C (rxn_008), while at higher hydrothermal temperatures it decarboxylates to 4-aminobutanal (rxn_018), connecting the proto-metabolic and Strecker pathways.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_018\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Proline", "overall_strategy": "Multi-environment synthesis network for L-proline integrating three established paradigms: (1) Sutherland cyanosulfidic photoredox chemistry producing pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile via reductive homologation of HCN and acetylene; (2) proto-metabolic hydrothermal r-TCA cycle analog producing alpha-ketoglutarate, then glutamate, glutamate-5-semialdehyde, and P5C following the biological biosynthetic logic (Stubbs & Moran); (3) Strecker-type chemistry via 1-pyrroline intermediate. Hub molecules (HCN, pyruvate, alpha-ketoglutarate, pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, P5C) create convergence points. Glutamate-5-semialdehyde serves as a critical branch point feeding both the P5C reduction route and the Strecker route via thermal decarboxylation to 4-aminobutanal. Chiral enrichment via calcite-mediated differential adsorption and proline-catalyzed amplification (Blackmond). Environmental flow: Hydrothermal CO2 fixation \u2192 Surface cyanosulfidic/Strecker chemistry \u2192 Biochemical assembly and chiral selection.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H2", "iupac_name": "ethyne", "common_name": "acetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "formaldehyde", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamate-5-semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO3/c6-4(5(8)9)2-1-3-7/h3-4H,1-2,6H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H7NO3", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H7NO3/c7-3-1-2-4(6-3)5(8)9/h3H,1-2H2,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C3H3N", "iupac_name": "2-propenenitrile", "common_name": "acrylonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H3N/c1-2-3-4/h2H,1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C5H7N3", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedinitrile", "common_name": "2-aminopentanedinitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C5H8N2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "common_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8N2/c6-4-5-2-1-3-7-5/h5,7H,1-3H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C4H9NO", "iupac_name": "4-aminobutanal", "common_name": "4-aminobutanal", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO/c5-3-1-2-4-6/h4H,1-3,5H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C4H7N", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole", "common_name": "1-pyrroline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7N/c1-2-4-5-3-1/h5H,1-4H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_023", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "DL-proline (racemic)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_024", "formula": "C5H9NO2", "iupac_name": "(S)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid", "common_name": "L-proline", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO2/c7-5(8)4-2-1-3-6-4/h4,6H,1-3H2,(H,7,8)/t4-/m0/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_025", "formula": "C5H10N2O", "iupac_name": "pyrrolidine-2-carboxamide", "common_name": "prolinamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2O/c6-5(8)4-2-1-3-7-4/h4,7H,1-3H2,(H2,6,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline vent fluid, pH 9-11, H2-rich serpentinization fluid"}, "mechanism": "CO2 adsorbs onto the greigite surface, which is structurally analogous to biological [Fe4S4] clusters. H2 dissociatively adsorbs on the mineral, providing hydride equivalents that reduce CO2 to formate via a surface-bound formate intermediate.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is one of the most well-established hydrothermal prebiotic reactions. Preiner et al. (2020) demonstrated native iron and Fe-Ni alloys reduce CO2 to formate, pyruvate, and acetate under alkaline hydrothermal conditions. Roldan et al. (2015) showed greigite electrochemically reduces CO2 to formate at low overpotentials, mimicking the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type reduction of formate to formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-470K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "FTT conditions in subseafloor hydrothermal systems"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced on magnetite surfaces via Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) hydrogenation. The carboxylate is activated on the oxide surface and reduced stepwise through a surface-bound formyl species to formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "McCollom & Seewald (2007) and He et al. (2019) demonstrated FTT synthesis produces formaldehyde and other oxygenated C1 species from CO/formate + H2 on magnetite under hydrothermal conditions. Magnetite provides both catalytic surface and reducing equivalents."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to pyruvate on Fe minerals", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and native iron", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 9-11, alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions"}, "mechanism": "Multi-step reduction of CO2 via sequential C1 additions on iron mineral surfaces. Formate and CO intermediates undergo carbonyl insertion and hydrogenation steps to build up to the C3 alpha-keto acid pyruvate. Native iron provides strong reducing potential.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2017) demonstrated the synthesis of pyruvate from CO2 and H2 on iron-containing minerals under mild aqueous conditions. Preiner et al. (2020) showed that native iron and Ni-Fe alloys in alkaline aqueous conditions at 100\u00b0C generate pyruvate alongside formate and acetate from CO2 and H2. This represents a prebiotically plausible carbon fixation pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Glyoxylate-pyruvate aldol condensation to alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-380K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "FeS minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9, mild aqueous conditions, Fe2+ in solution"}, "mechanism": "Aldol-type condensation between pyruvate and glyoxylate proceeds through a mineral-surface-mediated enolization of pyruvate, followed by nucleophilic addition to glyoxylate. Subsequent decarboxylation of the initial C5 beta-keto diacid intermediate yields alpha-ketoglutarate. The reaction is analogous to steps of the non-enzymatic r-TCA cycle.", "reasoning": "Stubbs et al. (2020) demonstrated that pyruvate and glyoxylate react under mild aqueous conditions to form alpha-ketoglutarate through an aldol-decarboxylation sequence, recapitulating key r-TCA cycle steps without enzymes. Moran and colleagues (Muchowska et al., 2019) showed that Fe2+ and other simple metal ions catalyze an 11-reaction network including this transformation. FeS mineral surfaces facilitate the enolization step."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["green rust (fougerite)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-380K", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "green rust (mixed-valence Fe oxyhydroxide)", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 8-10, H2-rich, NH4+ available from hydrothermal fluid"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia attacks the carbonyl carbon of alpha-ketoglutarate to form a carbinolamine, which dehydrates to an imine (Schiff base). The imine is then reduced by H2 activated on the green rust surface, yielding glutamate. Green rust provides both the mineral template and electronic conductivity for hydride transfer.", "reasoning": "Barge et al. (2019) demonstrated reductive amination of alpha-keto acids in the presence of ammonia and mixed-valence iron minerals under alkaline hydrothermal conditions. The literature review explicitly states that alpha-ketoglutarate reacts with an amine donor to form glutamate as a step congruent with modern biochemistry. Green rust (fougerite) has been proposed as a mineral precursor to Fe-S enzymes involved in the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate with glycine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350K (80\u00b0C)", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "AlK(SO4)2 or pyrite surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "pH 7-9, 4 hours reaction time, 44% yield"}, "mechanism": "Glycine donates its amino group to alpha-ketoglutarate via a pyridoxal-independent transamination. The reaction proceeds through a geminal diamine intermediate or direct amine transfer facilitated by the metal ion catalyst. Glycine is converted to glyoxylate, creating a catalytic recycling loop.", "reasoning": "The literature explicitly states: 'The synthesis of glutamate from alpha-ketoglutarate and glycine achieved a 44% yield in 4 hours at 80\u00b0C in the presence of AlK(SO4)2.' This is a key step in the proto-metabolic pathway. Transamination reactions between alpha-keto acids and amino acids are documented under mild prebiotic conditions (Muchowska et al., 2019). The glyoxylate byproduct feeds back into rxn_004, creating an autocatalytic loop."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Partial reduction of glutamate to glutamate-5-semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["green rust (fougerite)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-400K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "green rust, Fe2+ ions", "aqueous": true, "other": "H2-rich reducing environment, moderately alkaline pH"}, "mechanism": "The terminal carboxylic acid of glutamate is selectively reduced to an aldehyde on the green rust surface. The mixed-valence iron mineral activates H2 as a hydride source. The reaction is regioselective because the alpha-carboxylate is stabilized by chelation with the amino group and the mineral surface, leaving the distal gamma-carboxylate exposed for reduction.", "reasoning": "This partial reduction mirrors the biological glutamate-5-semialdehyde dehydrogenase reaction. While this specific prebiotic transformation remains experimentally challenging\u2014acknowledged as an open question in the literature\u2014green rust (fougerite) provides the electronic conductivity and mixed-valence iron centers needed for selective 2-electron reduction. Nitschke & Russell (2013) proposed that green rust minerals could mediate such selective reductions at alkaline vents. The research notes that Fe2+ and transition metal ions facilitate the reduction of P5C, implying the reverse direction is also accessible under more reducing conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Spontaneous cyclization of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to P5C", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_007"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "Spontaneous intramolecular condensation, pH 5-9"}, "mechanism": "The alpha-amino group of glutamate-5-semialdehyde attacks the gamma-aldehyde intramolecularly, forming a cyclic carbinolamine that dehydrates to give the Schiff base delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C). This is a thermodynamically favorable intramolecular condensation driven by the entropic advantage of five-membered ring formation.", "reasoning": "The literature explicitly states: 'Glutamate-5-semialdehyde, an intermediate formed by the partial reduction of glutamate, spontaneously cyclizes to form delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C).' This is a well-established spontaneous reaction in both biochemistry and prebiotic chemistry, requiring no catalyst. The five-membered ring formation is kinetically and thermodynamically favored (Baldwin's rules: 5-exo-trig cyclization)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Reduction of P5C to DL-proline", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm to moderate", "catalyst": "Fe2+ ions in solution", "aqueous": true, "other": "Reducing environment with available H2 or Fe2+ as electron donor"}, "mechanism": "The C=N imine bond of P5C is reduced by H2 activated by dissolved Fe2+ ions or by direct hydride transfer from Fe2+-mediated H2 heterolysis. The reduction yields the saturated pyrrolidine ring of proline. This produces a racemic mixture (DL-proline).", "reasoning": "The literature states: 'The reduction of P5C by H2 or transition metal ions (e.g., Fe2+) yields proline.' This final reduction step mirrors the biological pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase reaction. Under the reducing conditions of the Hadean Earth, with abundant dissolved Fe2+ and H2 from serpentinization, this reduction is thermodynamically favorable."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Copper-catalyzed HCN-acetylene coupling to acrylonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I)/Cu(II) minerals (cuprite/tenorite)", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation, cyanosulfidic conditions"}, "mechanism": "Cu(I) activates acetylene by coordination, enabling nucleophilic addition of cyanide to form acrylonitrile (2-propenenitrile). UV light drives the Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycle, regenerating the active Cu(I) species. The reaction proceeds through a vinyl-copper intermediate.", "reasoning": "The Sutherland group established that copper-catalyzed cross-coupling of HCN and acetylene generates acrylonitrile as a key C3 building block in the cyanosulfidic network. The literature states: 'A critical step in the assembly of the five-carbon skeleton of proline is the copper-catalyzed cross-coupling of hydrogen cyanide and acetylene. This reaction generates acrylonitrile, which then undergoes further reductive homologation.' UV-driven Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycling is the energy source (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Cyanosulfidic reductive homologation to 2-aminopentanedinitrile", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I)/Cu(II) minerals", "stibnite (Sb2S3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) photoredox, H2S as stoichiometric reductant", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation, mildly alkaline pH"}, "mechanism": "Acrylonitrile undergoes reductive homologation with HCN in the presence of H2S as the stoichiometric reductant. H2S reduces the cyanide adduct through a thiocyanate intermediate, extending the carbon chain. The process involves: (1) conjugate addition of HCN to acrylonitrile to give a C4 dinitrile, (2) further reductive cyanide addition driven by UV/Cu cycling, (3) reductive amination at the alpha-position to yield the five-carbon 2-aminopentanedinitrile.", "reasoning": "The Sutherland cyanosulfidic pathway uses reductive homologation of HCN derivatives with H2S as the reductant to build up carbon skeletons. The literature states: 'Reductive homologation of acrylonitrile in the presence of H2S as a reductant leads to the formation of 2-aminopentanedinitrile.' This is part of the network that simultaneously produces nucleotide, amino acid, and lipid precursors (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Intramolecular cyclization of 2-aminopentanedinitrile to pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-360K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pool; concentration drives ring closure"}, "mechanism": "The free amino group attacks one of the terminal nitrile carbons intramolecularly, forming a five-membered pyrrolidine ring with loss of NH3 or via an amidine intermediate. Montmorillonite clay concentrates the substrate by intercalation and provides an acidic surface that activates the nitrile toward nucleophilic attack. Wet-dry cycling increases the effective concentration.", "reasoning": "The literature identifies pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile as the immediate alpha-aminonitrile precursor formed by intramolecular cyclization of the dinitrile intermediate. The ring closure problem is noted as a key challenge: 'The entropic barrier to ring closure in dilute solution is a major bottleneck. Researchers are currently investigating whether mineral surfaces or the concentrated environment of evaporative basins could have overcome this barrier.' Montmorillonite has the highest molecular affinity for proline among minerals of prebiotic interest and its interlayer spaces provide a confined environment facilitating cyclization."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to prolinamide", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_025"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (acid catalysis in interlayer)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Neutral to mildly alkaline pH, partial hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile undergoes partial hydrolysis on the montmorillonite surface. Water attacks the electrophilic nitrile carbon, forming an iminol intermediate that tautomerizes to the amide (prolinamide). The clay surface provides Br\u00f8nsted acid sites that activate the nitrile toward nucleophilic addition of water.", "reasoning": "The literature identifies prolinamide as 'a stable amide that has been detected in simulated prebiotic synthesis' and states it 'serves as a key precursor for the formation of proline-containing cyclic dipeptides under wet-dry cycling conditions.' The stepwise hydrolysis nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid is well-established, with the amide being a kinetically accessible intermediate. Montmorillonite's high affinity for proline and its derivatives facilitates this transformation."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Hydrolysis of prolinamide to DL-proline via pH oscillation", "inputs": ["mol_025", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["calcite (CaCO3)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "340-360K (80\u00b0C)", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "calcite, pH oscillation between 7 and 11", "aqueous": true, "other": "Wet-dry cycles, evaporitic pool with calcite shores"}, "mechanism": "The amide bond of prolinamide is hydrolyzed to the free carboxylic acid under oscillating pH conditions. At high pH, hydroxide attacks the amide carbonyl; the return to neutral pH drives the equilibrium toward the free acid. Calcite dissolution and reprecipitation provides the pH oscillation. The elevated temperature (80\u00b0C) accelerates the hydrolysis kinetics.", "reasoning": "The literature states that 'In the synthesis of Cyclo-Pro-Pro from prolinamide at 80\u00b0C, the highest yields were achieved by oscillating the pH between 7 and 11.' Calcite has 'a remarkable enhancing effect' on the yield of proline-related products, increasing relative yield by 2.23-fold. pH oscillation models driven by calcite dissolution/precipitation cycles are prebiotically plausible in evaporitic settings."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Direct hydrolysis of pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile to DL-proline", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_023"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, mildly alkaline pH", "aqueous": true, "other": "Prolonged heating in evaporitic basin, >80\u00b0C"}, "mechanism": "Complete hydrolysis of the nitrile group through the amide intermediate to the carboxylic acid under sustained heating. At elevated temperature and mildly alkaline pH, the hydrolysis proceeds through both the amide and direct pathways. Montmorillonite provides acid-base catalytic sites and concentrates the substrate.", "reasoning": "The literature states that 'the hydrolysis of the nitrile intermediate represents a significant kinetic bottleneck, often requiring elevated temperatures (>80\u00b0C) or the presence of mineral catalysts to achieve meaningful yields.' Direct complete hydrolysis (nitrile \u2192 acid) is the net transformation of rxn_013 + rxn_014 and is achievable with sufficient time and temperature. Montmorillonite provides the necessary catalytic surface."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": true, "other": "Neutral to mildly alkaline pH (7-9)"}, "mechanism": "Classic Strecker synthesis: (1) formaldehyde condenses with ammonia to form an imine (methylenimine), (2) HCN adds to the imine to form aminoacetonitrile (alpha-aminonitrile), (3) hydrolysis of the nitrile yields glycine. Montmorillonite concentrates the reactants and catalyzes the hydrolysis step.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is described in the literature as 'the classical model for prebiotic amino acid formation, involving the reaction of an aldehyde or ketone with ammonia and hydrogen cyanide.' The synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde by this route is one of the most well-established prebiotic reactions (Miller, 1957; Strecker, 1850). Montmorillonite catalysis of amino acid formation is well-documented."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Formose reaction: formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ca(OH)2 / borate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline conditions, borate stabilization of intermediates"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde self-condensation via the formose reaction. Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo an umpolung aldol condensation: one serves as the nucleophilic enolate equivalent (activated by base) and the other as the electrophilic aldehyde. Borate minerals complex with the product glycolaldehyde, stabilizing it against further uncontrolled polymerization.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction producing sugars from formaldehyde is a well-established prebiotic pathway. The literature mentions 'Formose Reaction: n H2CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)2 or borate).' Borate minerals are critical for stabilizing sugars and preventing tar formation (Ricardo et al., 2004). Glycolaldehyde is the simplest sugar and serves as a key intermediate."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of glutamate-5-semialdehyde to 4-aminobutanal", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_021", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "pyrite surface, Fe2+ ions", "aqueous": true, "other": "Elevated temperature favors decarboxylation over cyclization"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-amino acid decarboxylation of glutamate-5-semialdehyde releases CO2 and produces 4-aminobutanal. The decarboxylation is facilitated by the alpha-amino group acting as an electron sink (analogous to PLP-dependent decarboxylation). At temperatures >100\u00b0C, the decarboxylation rate can compete with the intramolecular cyclization to P5C. Pyrite surface Lewis acid sites activate the carboxylate.", "reasoning": "Thermal decarboxylation of alpha-amino acids is well-documented under hydrothermal conditions (Li & Brill, 2003). Glutamate-5-semialdehyde possesses an alpha-amino acid moiety susceptible to decarboxylation. This creates a critical branch point in the network: at lower temperatures G5SA cyclizes to P5C (rxn_008), while at higher hydrothermal temperatures it decarboxylates to 4-aminobutanal, which feeds the Strecker pathway. This connection between the proto-metabolic and Strecker routes is a novel but chemically sound prediction."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Intramolecular cyclization of 4-aminobutanal to 1-pyrroline", "inputs": ["mol_021"], "outputs": ["mol_022", "mol_007"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": true, "other": "Spontaneous in aqueous solution at neutral to mildly acidic pH"}, "mechanism": "The primary amine of 4-aminobutanal attacks the aldehyde carbon intramolecularly, forming a cyclic hemiaminal that dehydrates to give 1-pyrroline (3,4-dihydro-2H-pyrrole). This is a thermodynamically favorable 5-exo-trig cyclization following Baldwin's rules.", "reasoning": "The literature explicitly describes this reaction: '4-aminobutanal can undergo intramolecular condensation to form 1-pyrroline.' This is a well-known spontaneous reaction in organic chemistry. The five-membered ring formation is both kinetically and thermodynamically favorable. No catalyst is required."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Strecker addition of HCN to 1-pyrroline forming pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_022", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": true, "other": "Neutral to mildly alkaline pH, evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (from HCN) to the electrophilic C=N of 1-pyrroline (cyclic imine). The cyanide attacks the iminium carbon, forming the alpha-aminonitrile pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. This is a standard Strecker-type addition to a cyclic imine. Montmorillonite concentrates both reactants.", "reasoning": "The literature describes this as a key step: 'The addition of HCN to this cyclic imine produces pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, which is then hydrolyzed to proline.' The Strecker addition to cyclic imines is well-established in prebiotic chemistry. This creates the second convergence point at pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile (also formed by the cyanosulfidic route, rxn_012)."}, {"id": "rxn_021", "name": "Enantiomeric enrichment of DL-proline to L-proline on calcite", "inputs": ["mol_023"], "outputs": ["mol_024"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "calcite chiral crystal faces, proline-catalyzed amplification", "aqueous": true, "other": "Chiral calcite (2-1-4) and (0-1-4) faces selectively adsorb D- and L-enantiomers respectively; subsequent proline-catalyzed feedback amplifies initial ee"}, "mechanism": "Two-stage chiral enrichment: (1) Differential adsorption\u2014DL-proline solution contacts calcite crystal faces that are inherently chiral. The (2-1-4) and (0-1-4) faces of calcite selectively adsorb one enantiomer, creating a solution enriched in the other. (2) Catalytic amplification\u2014the enantiomerically enriched proline catalyzes asymmetric aldol reactions (e.g., with glyceraldehyde), creating chiral products that feed back to further enrich L-proline through kinetic resolution in transamination reactions mediated by proline-containing dipeptides.", "reasoning": "The literature extensively discusses proline's role in homochirality: 'L-proline (as an N-terminal residue in dipeptides like Pro-Val) reacts preferentially with L-glyceraldehyde' (Blackmond and Sutherland groups). 'Even a small initial enantioenrichment of proline\u2014perhaps through chiral mineral surfaces like calcite\u2014could have been amplified through catalytic feedback loops, leading to the homochirality observed in modern biology.' Hazen et al. (2001) demonstrated that calcite crystal faces show enantioselective adsorption of amino acids. The amplification mechanism via proline-catalyzed aldol reactions and kinetic resolution is documented by Blackmond (2004, 2010)."}, {"id": "rxn_022", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite, FeS", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline vent conditions, pH 9-11"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is reduced to formate on greigite, then further reduced and carboxylated to form glyoxylate (oxoacetate). This two-step process involves the formation of a surface-bound CO/formyl species from formate, followed by carboxylation with a second CO2 molecule.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylate is a central metabolite in the non-enzymatic r-TCA cycle. Muchowska et al. (2019) and Stubbs et al. (2020) include glyoxylate as a key intermediate produced from CO2 reduction on iron minerals. While the direct formation of glyoxylate from CO2 requires more complex surface chemistry than formate formation, it is a necessary component of the proto-metabolic network. The alkaline hydrothermal environment provides the thermodynamic driving force."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathway (direct hydrolysis)", "description": "The primary cyanosulfidic route following Sutherland's systems chemistry. HCN and acetylene (from volcanic emissions) are coupled via Cu-catalyzed photoredox to form acrylonitrile, which is reductively homologated with H2S to 2-aminopentanedinitrile. Intramolecular cyclization on montmorillonite yields pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, which is directly hydrolyzed to DL-proline, then enantiomerically enriched to L-proline on calcite.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_015", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_017", "mol_018", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Cyanosulfidic via Prolinamide Intermediate", "description": "A variant of P1 where pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile is partially hydrolyzed to prolinamide, then further hydrolyzed to proline under pH-oscillating conditions with calcite catalysis. This route is slower but achieves higher selectivity.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_017", "mol_018", "mol_019", "mol_025"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Proto-metabolic Reductive Amination Pathway", "description": "Full hydrothermal proto-metabolic route: CO2 is fixed to pyruvate and glyoxylate, which condense to alpha-ketoglutarate (r-TCA analog). Reductive amination yields glutamate, which is partially reduced to G5SA, cyclizes to P5C, and is reduced to proline. This pathway mirrors modern biochemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_022", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Proto-metabolic Transamination Pathway", "description": "Similar to P3 but uses glycine (from surface Strecker synthesis) as the amino donor instead of ammonia. This pathway demonstrates the essential Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Hydrothermal interconnection.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_016", "rxn_003", "rxn_022", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_013", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_014", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Strecker Pathway via 1-Pyrroline (from G5SA decarboxylation)", "description": "A hybrid pathway where hydrothermal proto-metabolism produces glutamate-5-semialdehyde, which undergoes thermal decarboxylation (instead of cyclization to P5C) to yield 4-aminobutanal. This spontaneously cyclizes to 1-pyrroline, which undergoes Strecker HCN addition to form pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, converging with the cyanosulfidic route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_022", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_018", "rxn_019", "rxn_020", "rxn_015", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_015", "mol_021", "mol_022", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Strecker-1-Pyrroline via Transamination Branch", "description": "Variant of P5 using glycine-mediated transamination (rxn_006) instead of reductive amination (rxn_005) to form glutamate. Demonstrates the redundancy of amino group sources.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_016", "rxn_003", "rxn_022", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_018", "rxn_019", "rxn_020", "rxn_015", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_012", "mol_015", "mol_021", "mol_019"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Full Hydrothermal-to-Surface CO2 Fixation \u2192 Glycine \u2192 Transamination", "description": "Complete environmental trajectory: hydrothermal CO2 fixation produces formate and formaldehyde, which are transported to surface pools where Strecker synthesis produces glycine. Glycine returns to hydrothermal environment for transamination with alpha-ketoglutarate, producing glutamate that proceeds through P5C to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_016", "rxn_022", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_013", "mol_012", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Formaldehyde Hub to Glycolaldehyde Route", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde, then surface formose reaction to glycolaldehyde, which serves as a hub for further chemistry. Glycolaldehyde feeds into the broader prebiotic network. Combined with Strecker and proto-metabolic pathways for proline via glycine transamination route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_017", "rxn_016", "rxn_022", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_020", "mol_013", "mol_012", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Cyanosulfidic to Strecker Convergence at Pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile", "description": "Demonstrates the convergence of the cyanosulfidic and Strecker-1-pyrroline routes at pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile. Takes the proto-metabolic route to G5SA, decarboxylates to 4-aminobutanal, forms 1-pyrroline, adds HCN (Strecker), and then follows the prolinamide hydrolysis branch.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_022", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_018", "rxn_019", "rxn_020", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_015", "mol_022", "mol_019", "mol_025"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Glyoxylate Recycling Autocatalytic Loop", "description": "Demonstrates the autocatalytic nature of the proto-metabolic network. Glyoxylate produced as a byproduct of the transamination (rxn_006) feeds back into the pyruvate-glyoxylate condensation (rxn_004), creating a self-amplifying cycle. Each turn of the cycle produces one glutamate equivalent that proceeds to proline.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_022", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_021"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_014", "mol_016"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_019", "mol_016"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_004", "description": "HCN is a primary carbon/nitrogen source feeding into multiple routes: cyanosulfidic acrylonitrile formation, Strecker glycine synthesis, and Strecker addition to 1-pyrroline. Derived from volcanic/atmospheric processes.", "incoming_reactions": [], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_016", "rxn_020"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "description": "Pyruvate is the central C3 alpha-keto acid hub. Produced by hydrothermal CO2 fixation, it feeds into the r-TCA-like condensation with glyoxylate to build the C5 skeleton of proline precursors.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "description": "Alpha-ketoglutarate is the critical C5 convergence point. Formed from pyruvate + glyoxylate condensation, it is the branch point for both reductive amination (with NH3) and transamination (with glycine) to glutamate. All proto-metabolic routes pass through this hub.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_019", "description": "Pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile is the major convergence point where the cyanosulfidic pathway (rxn_012) and the Strecker-1-pyrroline pathway (rxn_020) meet. It is the immediate alpha-aminonitrile precursor to proline.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_012", "rxn_020"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_013", "rxn_015"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_016", "description": "Delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate (P5C) is the central branch point of the proto-metabolic pathway. Formed by spontaneous cyclization of G5SA, it is reduced directly to proline. P5C is also a biological branch point to glutamate and arginine.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_015", "description": "Glutamate-5-semialdehyde is a critical branch point: at moderate temperatures it cyclizes to P5C (rxn_008), while at higher hydrothermal temperatures it decarboxylates to 4-aminobutanal (rxn_018), connecting the proto-metabolic and Strecker pathways.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_018"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 499311.537027359, "success": true, "error_message": null}
