: \"P10\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_003\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_022\": 0.70,\n                \"rxn_004\": 0.70,\n                \"rxn_006\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_007\": 0.55,\n                \"rxn_008\": 0.95,\n                \"rxn_009\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_021\": 0.70\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.73,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n            \"feedback\": \"The autocatalytic loop concept via glyoxylate recycling (rxn_006 produces glyoxylate that feeds back into rxn_004) is an elegant feature that mirrors the self-sustaining nature of the r-TCA cycle. This is conceptually important for demonstrating network robustness. However, the loop depends on the continuous supply of glycine as an amine donor and suffers from the rxn_007 bottleneck. The autocatalytic nature may be partially self-limiting due to product inhibition.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_004\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Quantify the autocatalytic amplification factor\", \"Consider whether the glyoxylate loop can sustain itself against hydrolysis losses\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"This is an outstanding synthesis network for L-proline that demonstrates sophisticated integration of three major prebiotic chemistry paradigms: Sutherland cyanosulfidic systems chemistry, Stubbs & Moran proto-metabolic hydrothermal pathways, and Strecker-type chemistry. The network excels in several dimensions:\\n\\n**Strengths:**\\n1. **Exceptional literature alignment** (0.93): The network directly implements the three key scenarios identified in the deep research\u2014cyanosulfidic photoredox, proto-metabolic r-TCA analogs, and Strecker synthesis\u2014with correct intermediates and conditions. The Blackmond chiral amplification reference is appropriate.\\n2. **Hub molecule selection** is excellent: HCN, pyruvate, AKG, pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile, and P5C are all identified as critical branch points in the literature.\\n3. **Convergence at pyrrolidine-2-carbonitrile** from both cyanosulfidic and Strecker routes is a powerful network feature, demonstrating that multiple geochemical environments could produce the same key intermediate.\\n4. **10 distinct pathways** provide genuine redundancy, which is essential for prebiotic plausibility.\\n5. **The glyoxylate recycling loop** (P10) adds an autocatalytic dimension.\\n\\n**Weaknesses:**\\n1. **rxn_007 (glutamate \u2192 G5SA)** is the single most problematic reaction, appearing in 8 of 10 pathways. This selective partial reduction has no demonstrated prebiotic analog and represents a significant gap between abiotic chemistry and the biological pathway.\\n2. **rxn_002 (formate \u2192 formaldehyde)** in hydrothermal conditions faces thermodynamic challenges.\\n3. **rxn_004** oversimplifies the pyruvate-to-AKG conversion.\\n4. **rxn_021 (enantiomeric enrichment on calcite)** needs stronger mechanistic support. The literature discusses calcite's effect on dipeptide yields but direct chiral resolution of free proline on calcite is not well-demonstrated.\\n5. **Some mineral catalysts are unspecified** in hydrothermal reactions (e.g., rxn_004, rxn_005, rxn_007).\\n\\n**Recommendation:** The cyanosulfidic pathways (P1, P2) are the most chemically robust and best-supported. P5 and P9 provide excellent cross-environment connectivity. The proto-metabolic route (P3) needs experimental validation of the glutamate-to-G5SA step. Overall, this is an impressive, literature-grounded network that merits approval.\",\n    \"approved\": true,\n    \"hub_quality\": 0.92,\n    \"convergence_quality\": 0.90\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_